<HEADLINE> Lebanese Intellectuals Support Accused Singer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's intellectuals on
DPA288WSD006S05PEQU03:0003:001316
Tuesday held a mass rally to declare solidarity with the
country's leading singer and composer Marcel Khalife accused of
allegedly insulting Islam.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of journalists, writers and politicians participated
in the rally, which was held at the headquarters of the
country's Press Association in Beirut, and signed a petition.
</P>
<P>
They said in the petition that the signatories assumed
responsibility for helping Khalife produce an album for which
he was facing blasphemy charges for including a Koranic verse
in one of his songs.
</P>
<P>
"If they decide to try Khalife, we will all go with him,"
novelist Elias Khouri told the rally.
</P>
<P>
Khalife, 49, is renowned in both Lebanon and the Arab
world. His songs were particularly popular among young Lebanese
during the country's 15-year civil war that ended in 1990.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Beirut's investigating magistrate Abdelrahman
Shihab accused Khalife of insulting Islam by incorporating verses
of the Koran into his song "Oh Father, It is I, Youssef."
</P>
<P>
In 1996, he faced a similar charge for the same song,
which is included in his 1995 album "Arabic Coffeepot", but
pressure from intellectuals and the then Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri convinced authorities to drop the case.
</P>
<P>
Khalife has been referred to a Beirut court and could face a
six-month to three-year sentence in jail if he is found guilty.
</P>
<P>
The Beirut prosecutor is studying the judge's indictment and
will set a date for a court hearing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
