<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SAID '99 Must Not Be Mere Talk Shop, S. African </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 4 (Xinhua) -- South African President Thabo
Mbeki has warned African leaders attending the third Southern
African International Dialog (SAID) to guard against turning the
conference into a mere talk shop.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki told the leaders that there was usually no action taken
after such discussions, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
As smart partners, everyone participating the conference should
answer the question, "what have we done to implement the decisions
we took to realize the perspective of smart partnership?" Mbeki
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly, the great advantage of this would be that it would
spur to action those like me who are great talkers and poor
doers," he said.
</P>
<P>
The South African president noted there would be no need for
the conference to continue if it would turn the leaders into
rapporteurs.
</P>
<P>
However, Mbeki noted that one of the serious challenges facing
African governments was of "little capacity".
</P>
<P>
"The last point I would like to make is that the more we report
to one another about what we are actually doing, the greater the
transparency among ourselves about our practical activity, the
more we will defeat rumor and prejudice and false knowledge which
in many instances create barriers of mistrust among ourselves," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
