<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Train Crash Death Toll Rises to 26 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The death toll has risen to 26 in
Tuesday's crash of two commuter trains in central London, rescue
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Rescuers were bringing in floodlights and cranes to sift
through the derailed and smashed carriages throughout the night.
</P>
<P>
Police said it could take at least 24 hours before they would
know how many bodies remained trapped in the wreckage and could
remove them.
</P>
<P>
"It's a long and laborious process. The trains are extensively
mangled," Deputy Assistant Commissioner Andy Trotter told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
The crash near London's Paddington main line station at the
peak of the morning rush hour also sent more than 130 people to
hospital, 26 of them with serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
It was the second fatal crash on the same stretch of line in
two years, sparking renewed concerns about the safety record of
Britain's rail system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
