<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Exercise "Nikiforos '99" Very </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides on Tuesday heaped praises on Cyprus' National Guards
annual military exercise "Nikiforos '99" which started in the day,
saying it was "very successful".
</P>
<P>
After watching part of the war game, he said it was a
combination of defensive and offensive moves in which all weapons
participated.
</P>
<P>
The military exercise, which started last Saturday, will last
six days.
</P>
<P>
Greek navy vessels, including a frigate and a submarine, and
Greek military aircraft, including two F-16 and two A-7 Corsair
and a C-130 with parachutists, took part in Tuesday's manoeuvres.
</P>
<P>
Asked to comment on Turkish claims the manoeuvres cause
instability in the region, Clerides replied "it seems Turkey is
somewhat concerned about strengthening our defenses with the
participation of the Greek air force."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Cyprus reached an agreement in November 1993 that
Greece will offer Cyprus land, sea and air cover in the event of
fresh Turkish attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
