<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls on All U.N. Members to Pay Dues in Full </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday called upon all member states to "pay their
dues in full, on time and without conditions," saying this is "the
only solution" to the world body's chronic financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The appeal came as Annan was addressing the Fifth Committee of
the General Assembly on how to improve the financial situation of
the United Nations, which, a non-profit organization, fully
depends on all member states for financial support.
</P>
<P>
"The only solution, quite simply, is that all member states
must honor their legal and moral obligations under the Charter and
pay their dues in full, on time and without conditions," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the meantime, I would ask the General Assembly to consider
temporarily suspending the provisions of the financial regulations
requiring the return of surpluses to the member states," he said.
"Though by no means answer to our problems, this step would help
to improve our chronic cash shortage."
</P>
<P>
The United States, the richest country in the world, is the
biggest debtor to the United Nations, owing the world body some
1.7 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The United States is again threatened this year within losing
its vote in the General Assembly next year if it doesn't pay an
estimated 350 million U.S. dollars by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress has held up payment of 1.5 billion U.S.
dollars for years, demanding that the United Nations streamline
its organization and institute a no-growth budget. Legislation
that would have paid off the bulk of the bills was vetoed last
year by U.S. President Bill Clinton because it contained unrelated
restrictions on U.S. spending for overseas family planning
organizations.
</P>
<P>
On the U.N. reform, he said, "We have come a long way together.
Nearly three years later, it is fair to say that we have made good
and determined progress."
</P>
<P>
"But it is equally fair to say that we have a long way to go
before we can pronounce ourselves satisfied," he said. "The
transformation of our United Nations has yet to attack what I see
as an overly burdensome and overly intrusive approach to
administration."
</P>
<P>
"The international community continues to turn to the United
Nations for our unique services," he said. "The world public
continue to place faith in us as an agent of peace and progress."
</P>
<P>
"All of us want a United Nations that works -- for peace, for
development, for human rights and more," he said. "I believe that
such a United Nations is well within our capacity. But to reach
the goals we share, there needs to be a better way of doing
business in this house." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
