<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Urged to Be Competitive in Globalization of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Africa needs trained staff,
lean and mean management structure as well as effective system to
benefit from the globalization in the insurance sector, a senior
Ethiopian official said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a workshop of African Insurance Educators and
Trainers, Nituk Frnrnr, Vice Minister of the Trade and Industry,
said that the success in Africa's efforts for development and
liberal economy would be strengthened by competitive insurance
industry.
</P>
<P>
Globalization had made all sectors but the insurance sector
more competitive, the vice minister said, adding that the fate of
small national insurance companies would be uncertain unless they
quickly build their capacities to be competitive.
</P>
<P>
Patrick Georgen, representative of the United Nations
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD), said at the meeting
that Africa should take precautionary measurers as markets opened
to foreign participation.
</P>
<P>
He said competitive distortions may appear because of
unbalanced market structures, depriving of the insurance industry
from the expected benefits of liberalization.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency reported Tuesday that a workshop of
African financial sector supervisory authorities that examines
financial regulations of the continent is underway here behind
closed doors.
</P>
<P>
The workshop was organized by the UNCTAD, the Association for
African Insurance Supervisory Authority, the African Insurance
Organization, the Ethiopian Insurance Corporation, and the
National Bank of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Some 49 participants from 31 African countries and the UNCTAD
are attending the workshops. 
</P>
</TEXT>
