<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Leaders Under Fire on Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Southern African leaders
attending the third Southern African International Dialog (SAID)
came under fire Tuesday for lacking the sense of urgency in the
development of the tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
Peace Parks Foundation chairman Anthony Rupet said if the
unemployment problems facing the region were to be solved, there
was need to quickly speed up the development of the tourism
industry.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is that there is no sense of urgency in Africa,"
Rupet pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"If they want to start creating employment, they have to start
thinking seriously about developing the industry and put a sense
of urgency into it," he said.
</P>
<P>
The other problem facing the region was lack of marketing of
the tourism facilities which had the potential to attract more
people, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the Peace Parks Foundation was in the process of
establishing guest houses in the region to accommodate more
tourists.
</P>
<P>
"But still there are no airports in most resort areas. Worse
still there are also no aeroplanes which can carry large numbers
of people, strengthening the point that the leaders are not
serious enough," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Peace Parks Foundation was a tourism organization dealing
with the development of tourism in different regions including the
Southern African Development Community (SADC). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
