<HEADLINE> UK Conservatives Want Big EU Treaty Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain's opposition Conservative
party committed itself Tuesday to negotiating far-reaching changes
to the Treaty of Rome, founding charter of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Foreign affairs spokesman John Maples said at the party's
annual conference in Blackpool that the only decisions that should
have to be made at a European level were those involving the EU's
"core function" of free trade and free markets, Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
He promised that when the party returned to government, it
would negotiate a treaty amendment "to allow each country the
freedom to decide for itself whether or not to apply new European
legislation."
</P>
<P>
Maples did not mention withdrawal from the EU as a possibility
and denied his push for a more flexible EU, first heralded by
party leader William Hague in a speech in Hungary earlier this
summer, was anti-European.
</P>
<P>
Maples said an amendment to the Treaty of Rome was needed to
"stop the slide to a superstate" in Europe and protect Britain
from "every anti-business, nanny state, interfering regulation"
from the European Commission.
</P>
<P>
"If the European Union develops into a Federal superstate, then
Britain will simply be a province of that superstate," the agency
quoted Maples as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
