<HEADLINE> Blair Promises "Fullest" Train Crash Inquiry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The British government Tuesday
promised a public inquiry into the causes of the fatal train crash
near London's Paddington station.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair expressed his condolences to the
families and friends of those people who were killed and injured
in the collision near the site of the 1997 Southall rail crash.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Blair promised the latest accident would be
thoroughly investigated.
</P>
<P>
"I am absolutely appalled by what is a truly dreadful tragedy,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister John Prescott also visited the crash
scene and promised a public inquiry.
</P>
<P>
The death toll in Britain's worst rail accident in a decade was
expected to rise from eight Tuesday after police said more bodies
were trapped in the wreckage of two trains in central London.
</P>
