<HEADLINE> Mozambique Privatizes Nacala Port and Railway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique has privatized Nacala
port and railway system (CFM), which links Mozambique and
neighboring Malawi, by granting its management to Nacala Corridor
Development Company (SDCN).
</P>
<P>
According to an SDCN press release on Tuesday, the company
will be granted a 15 year lease to operate and manage the port,and
railway.
</P>
<P>
SDCN, whose board of directors is chaired by Former Mozambican
Defense Minister Alberto Chipande, is a consortium of Mozambican
companies (including CFM itself) and foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
Among the foreign stakeholders are the American Railway
Development Corporation and Edlows of the United States, Tertir
and Somafel of Portugal, and Congifer and SAE-International of
France.
</P>
<P>
CFM and SDCN will also manage Malawi railways. The Malawi
Privatization Commission announced in June that the CFM/SDCN bid
had won the privatization tender.
</P>
<P>
Thus the entire operation, from unloading goods at the port of
Nacala through to their final destination in Malawi, and vice
versa, can be run in a smooth and seamless fashion.  
</P>
</TEXT>
