<HEADLINE> U.N. Transitional Administration in E.Timor Unveiled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Tuesday proposed the establishment of a United Nations
Transitional Administration of East Timor (UNTAET) for its
transfer to independence.
</P>
<P>
In a written report to the Security Council, Annan said the
UNTAET would consist of 8,950 troops, 200 military observers,
1,640 international police and a civilian police unit of 1,250
officers and other segments.
</P>
<P>
With a function of maintaining law and order in East Timor and
administering the territory, the UNTAET is projected to stay there
for two to three years.
</P>
<P>
Operated under the authority of the Security Council and
exercised by the Secretary-General's special representative, the
body would be responsible for all aspects of the U.N. work in East
Timor, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Annan hopes that the UNTAET would be entrusted with a "robust
mandate." Apart from providing security, it would establish an
effective administration, assist in the civil and social services,
and support capacity-building for self-government.
</P>
<P>
He called on U.N. member states to provide experts and make
voluntary contributions to funding UNTAET activities.
</P>
<P>
The foreign ministers of Indonesia and Portugal reiterated
their agreement for the transfer of authority in East Timor to the
United Nations at a meeting on September 29, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
The total transfer is expected to be completed after
constitutional changes are done late this month or in early
November.
</P>
<P>
The report, covering the period from August 9 to October 4,
reviewed the situation in East Timor, where the U.N. authorized
multinational force (MNF) started to be deployed on September 20
with an unspecified number of troops from 14 countries.
</P>
<P>
The force, expected to reach 8,000 with a further number of
countries to join, will be replaced by a long-term U.N.
peace-keeping operation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
