<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Officials Hail Deal on Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
negotiators Tuesday hailed a newly-clinched deal on the
first-ever safe passage route between Gaza and the West Bank as an
important step for the revived peace process.
</P>
<P>
"It is in our interest to have the Palestinian population in a
state of economic and cultural satisfaction," Israeli Internal
Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami told reporters after signing a
protocol on the safe passage route with Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Minister of Civilian Affairs Jamal Tarif.
</P>
<P>
"I think this is good for the peace process. It is also good
for the stability between ourselves and the Palestinians as a
whole," Ben-Ami added.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the agreement, Palestinians can travel by
cars or buses between Gaza and the southern West Bank city of
Hebron along a 43-kilometer-long route after security checks,
ending decades of separation between the two areas.
</P>
<P>
Those Palestinians who are prevented from entering Israel can
also travel along the passage, but on buses escorted by Israeli
police. Only those wanted by Israel will be denied permits.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the people can move between Gaza and the West Bank by
going through the security procedure under the protocol. This is
the most important thing to us," Tarif said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians also regard the opening of the safe passage as
an important step toward the realization of their aspiration to an
independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
"The most important thing... is the geographic and demographic
unity between Gaza and the West Bank," PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat
said in Gaza, hours before the agreement was signed.
</P>
<P>
Differences over security arrangements on the road had
prevented the safe passage route from being opened last Sunday as
stipulated in the revised Wye interim agreement signed in Sharm
el-Sheikh, Egypt, one month ago.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have, however, downplayed the postponement. They
held intensive talks after the deadline was missed, and reached
agreement Monday night.
</P>
<P>
Asked if the agreement over the safe passage symbolizes the
recovery of the mutual trust, which was severely damaged in the
three years of rule under Israeli hard-line prime minister
Benjamin Netanyahu, Tarif said the trust building has begun ever
since the signing of the Sharm el-Sheikh agreement.
</P>
<P>
As for the concern expressed by Palestinians that Israel might
use the safe passage to arrest wanted Palestinians, Ben-Ami said
Israel never intends to create a kind of trap and ambush in order
to get hold of those Palestinians that Israel otherwise couldn't
get hold of.
</P>
<P>
Israel has given up its demand to keep the right in the
agreement to arrest Palestinian suspects on the road, but it was
granted ultimate authority on security issues, like the issue of
passage permits and security checks.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami stressed that the Israeli security concerns will be
exercised "in such a way that does not infringe upon the rights of
the Palestinians and the dignity of the Palestinians."
</P>
<P>
For his part, Tarif said the PNA has no doubt that the road is
under Israeli sovereignty. He pledged full Palestinian security
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami said at the ceremony that the two sides need "a few
days" to finalize all technical arrangements before the safe
passage can be opened.
</P>
<P>
Both officials said the two sides will start immediate
negotiations on the terms of the second safe passage route
stipulated in signed Israeli-Palestinian agreements.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami said the second route, which links Gaza and the
northern West Bank city of Ramallah, will be opened early next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
