<HEADLINE> Zambia Urged to Invest in Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has been
urged to invest in education to rescue the falling standards in
the sector.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Congress of Trade Unions (ZCTU) Secretary General
Sylvester Tembo said Tuesday that education receives the least
investment from the government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at celebrations to mark the International Teachers Day
at the city square of Kitwe in Copperbelt Province, Tembo said
that the Zambian education sector was the least supported in the
entire southern African region.
</P>
<P>
"Government should deliberately revamp the education sector by
turning around and invest heavily in the teachers," he said.
</P>
<P>
The congressman also condemned the trends where policies in the
 education sector are made without seeking consultation or an
input from teachers, adding such trends are unfair and should be
stopped.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Minister of Education Godfrey Miyanda released here
a joint statement with International Labor Organization, United
Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization, United
Nations Development Program and United Nations Children's Fund,
saying the world acknowledges the contribution of teachers across
the globe in awakening potential and fostering the fundamental
capacity of human beings to seek knowledge, disseminate
information and share their collective wisdom.
</P>
<P>
He said despite their poor working conditions, limited
resources and inadequate remuneration, teachers have helped the
world to move forward and therefore are entitled to active support
of the communication industry and the societies they serve.
</P>
<P>
He said with the scourge of child labor, free basic education
has been provided by teachers worldwide as a key to removing an
estimated 120 million children worldwide between the ages of five
and 14 years from full time work and providing for their social
integration.
</P>
<P>
Miyanda pledged to work and cooperate with teachers to achieve
the common objectives as teachers have a central role to play in
the education delivery system, especially in the development of
children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
