<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Former President Nyerere on Slow </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Physicians attending
Tanzanian former president Julius Nyerere, who has been in
critical condition at St. Thomas Hospital in London, said that he
is recovering slowly.
</P>
<P>
The doctors said a thorough medical examination on Nyerere,
suffering from leukemia, did not detect any other diseases
attacking him, the Tanzanian State House said in a bulletin issued
here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The 77-year-old African statesman, admitted to the hospital 11
days ago, was being troubled by malaria, jaundice and breathing
problems during the course of treatment, said the bulletin.
</P>
<P>
It said that all important parts of the body of Nyerere are
functioning properly and other new health problems cropped up
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The doctors said in a message faxed to the State House that
Nyerere's fever has been contained and his liver problem is almost
solved.
</P>
<P>
However, the doctors said that Nyerere still depends on life
support system, which helps him breathe and fight other health
complications.
</P>
<P>
The African (newspaper) said President Bill Clinton has pledged
to fly in American doctors to join the panel of British doctors.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government has expressed appreciation to Britain
and the United States for their medical assistance.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian High Commissioner to Britain, Abdulkadir Shareef, has
 expressed gratitude to the two countries, particularly during the
hard times Nyerere was experiencing.
</P>
<P>
Retired Tanzanian leader Rashid Kawawa, a close friend of
Nyerere, left capital Dar es Salaam for London to visit the ailing
former president.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday evening, prayers were conducted at Aga Khan Ismailia
Tembpe in Dar es Salaam wishing Nyerere a quick recovery as
anxiety grips the nation.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere led the then Tanganyika to independence from Britain in
1961 and masterminded its union Zanzibar isles in 1964 to form
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
After retiring as president in 1985, he played an advisory role
in both Tanzanian politics and African affairs. He has tirelessly
mediated Burundi peace talks since 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
