<HEADLINE> Earthquakes Hit Greece's Rhodes Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Two earthquakes rocked the
southeastern Greek island of Rhodes Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
With its epicenter in the sea region north of Rhodes, 410
kilometers southeast of Athens, the first earthquake registering
4.6 on the Richter scale occurred at 4:05 a.m. local time while
the second one measuring 5.2 on the Richter scale took place at
2:45 p.m. local time, said local press reports.
</P>
<P>
There were no immediate reports of damage or injures.
</P>
<P>
On September 7, a powerful earthquake hit Athens with its
epicenter being in the Parnitha region, some 20 kilometers
northwest of Athens.
</P>
<P>
A total of 143 people were killed and more than 2,000 others
injured and some 60,000 others left homeless in the earthquake,
which is estimated to cost Greece more than 200 billion drachmas
(about 645 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
