<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-05 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egyptian President Appoints New PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
on Tuesday appointed Atef Ebeid, minister of public business
sector, as the new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Ebeid, Mubarak asked him to form a new
government, the country's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ebeid told reporters after the meeting that he was given the
directives as the criteria for choosing the cabinet ministers and
that he will submit to the president a list of the ministers on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said he "would only allow those with high qualifications,
experience, success in previous jobs and integrity of character,
to serve in his cabinet."
</P>
<P>
The 67-year-old Ebeid holds a Ph.D. from Illinois University of
the United States and served several senior government posts
before he was appointed minister of public business sector.
</P>
<P>
Local reports have said the new cabinet will be sworn in
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The former cabinet headed by Kamal El-Ganzouri resigned in the
day after Mubarak was sworn in for a fourth consecutive six-year
term in office earlier at an extraordinary session of the
parliament, the People's Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak won about 94 percent "yes" votes in a yes-or-no,
uncontested referendum on September 26. Under Egypt's
constitution, the cabinet must resign to pave the way for the
formation of a new cabinet in the wake of a new presidential term
in office.
</P>
<P>
Ebeid, as minister of public business sector, was in charge of
the privatization program in the former government. His
appointment as the new prime minister demonstrated Mubarak's
determination and commitment to the economic reforms beginning in
1991, which have largely improved Egypt's economic landscape and
helped the country maintain one of the best economic performances
in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
Local media have anticipated a substantial cabinet reshuffle
due to what the media said the cabinet's failure to meet what the
people have hoped for and to achieve the ambitious goals set by
the president. 
</P>
</TEXT>
