<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Indonesia's New House Speaker Akbar Tandjung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Akbar Tandjung, general chairman
of the Golkar Party, was elected as the new speaker of Indonesia's
House of Representatives (DPR) on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
Born in Sibolga, North Sumatera Province, on August 14, 1945,
Akbar decided on a political career as early as his student days
at the University of Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
He moved to Jakarta halfway through his senior high school
study in 1962 and joined the Faculty of Technology of the
state-run university in 1964. Akbar once recalled that he entered
the university at a time when every student was expected to join
one of the many political organizations that had established bases
in campuses.
</P>
<P>
Akbar chose the Association of Muslim Students (HMI) and poured
his energy into the organization. One of the reasons that he took
his time to complete his study was because he was too busy playing
politics. He graduated only in 1983.
</P>
<P>
Akbar served as HMI chairman from 1972 to 1974, chairman of the
Indonesian Young Generation for Renewal from 1978 to 1979 and
chairman of the Indonesian National Youth Committee from 1978 to
1981.
</P>
<P>
He has been a member of Golkar (Functional Group), set up by a
group of military and civilian leaders in 1966, since his student
days and worked his way up the political ladder through the
various youth and student organizations he joined.
</P>
<P>
His first major break in Golkar came when he was appointed
deputy secretary-general in 1983 after helping Sudharmono get
elected as the party's chairman. Golkar has been dominating the
legislative body since the establishment of the New Order
administration led by former President Soeharto in 1967.
</P>
<P>
His two previous political mentors, former Golkar General
Chairman Sudharmono and Soeharto, saw Akbar as a skilled
administrator and a highly able organization man.
</P>
<P>
Sudharmono recruited Akbar as his deputy secretary-general when
he chaired the political organization from 1983 to 1988.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto enlisted Akbar as a member of his cabinet. In
1988-1993, he was state minister of youth affairs and sports and
in 1993-1998, he served as state minister of housing and
settlements.
</P>
<P>
When Soeharto was re-elected in March last year, Akbar was
again asked to serve in the cabinet, keeping his housing
portfolio.
</P>
<P>
Given his administrative and organizational qualities and
political skills, Akbar played a vital role in the meetings of the
People's Consultative Assembly (MPR), the country's highest
decision-making body, both in 1993 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
Akbar was one of the 14 members of the cabinet who wrote to
Soeharto on May 20 stating that they were not willing to serve in
his cabinet anymore. Soeharto resigned the next day.
</P>
<P>
When B.J. Habibie took power on May 21 last year, Akbar's
political capabilities were exalted and he was moved into the
inner circle as the powerful minister/state secretary for the new
president.
</P>
<P>
At the extraordinary congress of Golkar in July last year,
Akbar became the first general chairman of the political
organization to be elected by a secret ballot, beating former
Defense Minister Gen. (ret.) Edi Sudradjat. Golkar was officially
declared a political party in March this year.
</P>
<P>
In order to concentrate on the June 7 general election this
year, Akbar quit his cabinet post in early May. The party came in
second in the election with 120 seats, trailing behind the
Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle which got 153 seats in the
new House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Akbar married late in his life, at 35 years old, a factor which
again he attributed to his political activities. He met his wife,
Krisnina Maharani, from Surakarta, Central Java, when he was
active in the Indonesian National Youth Committee. The couple now
have three children, all girls. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional NATO Sub-Command Officially Operates in Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- A regional NATO sub headquarters,
officially known as "Joint Command South Center," Tuesday operated
at Tyrnavos near Larissa, central Greece.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a ceremony, Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos said that the upgrading of Greece's position in the
alliance also confirmed the country's role as a force for
stability, peace and security in the region.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the Tyrnavos sub-headquarters would be a center
for the exercise of NATO policy in the region.
</P>
<P>
U.S. General Wesley Clark, allied supreme commander, also said
at the ceremony that the activation was associated with many hopes
about the functioning of the "new NATO" and the consolidation of
security and cooperation in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Tyrnavos sub-headquarters is one of four southern NATO
sub-headquarters activated recently. When fully operational, it
will have 453 commissioned and non-commissioned officers and 815
civilian employees, half of whom will be Greek. 
</P>
