<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian House Elects New Speaker, Vice-Speakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Indonesian House
of Representatives (DPR) at midnight Tuesday elected Akbar
Tandjung, general chairman of the Golkar Party, as the new speaker
of the house.
</P>
<P>
With a consensus reached after consultations among leaders of
all the factions in the DPR, Akbar was named house speaker for the
1999-2004 tenure.
</P>
<P>
A.M. Fatwa, chairman of the National Mandate Party; Soetardjo
Soerjogoeritno, chairman of the Indonesian Democratic Party of
Struggle; Khofifah Indarparawansa, chairman of the National
Awakening Party; and Hamzah Haz, general chairman of the United
Development Party were elected as vice-speakers.
</P>
<P>
The DPR has a total of 500 members who serve for five years. It
exercises legislative authority, with 462 members directly elected
and 38 reserved for the Military/National Police whose members do
not vote.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-one of the 48 political parties which contested the June
7 general election gained seats in the DPR.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle won the election
with 153 seats.
</P>
<P>
The Golkar Party came in second with 120 seats, followed by the
United Development Party with 58 seats, the National Awakening
Party 51, the National Mandate Party 34, the Crescent Star Party
13 and the Justice Party seven.
</P>
<P>
The DPR meets at least once a year. All laws must have the
approval of the DPR, but the president has the power of absolute
veto. Members of the DPR have the right to submit draft bills
which require ratification by the president. The president may
enact ordinance in times of emergency, which however must be
either ratified or revoked by the DPR at its following session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek PM Urges Turkey to Show Deeds for Better </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis Tuesday urged neighboring Turkey to translate the
unprecedented good climate in Greek-Turkish relations into deeds
and decisions which would create a solid foundation for the
improvement of bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ruling Panhellenic Socialist Movement's
parliamentary group, Simitis said that such deeds and decisions
had not yet been forthcoming, but expressed the hope that Turkey
would take a substantial step to advance its European vocation and
support efforts being made for closer cooperation, the
semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
An impetus had been created that had given the neighboring
country the dilemma of choosing between peace and cooperation or a
gradual distancing from European structures and marginalization,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The premier stressed that Athens believed in Turkey's European
vocation but this entailed both rights and responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
Greek government spokesman Dimitris Reppas also noted at a
press briefing that for Turkey to be included in an EU candidate
country, it must fall into line with the decisions taken at the EU
summits in Luxembourg and Cardiff.
</P>
<P>
He said that in this case, Greece would have no objection to
upgrading relations between the EU and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Turkey have nearly gone to war three times in the
past 25 years for their disputes in the territorial waters, air
space limits, the delimitation of the continental shelf in the
Aegean Sea and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Greece has insisted that Turkey cannot join the EU unless it
improves its human rights record and relations with Greece as well
as not blocking Cyprus's accession to the EU.
</P>
<P>
The recent devastating earthquakes in Turkey and Greece have
provided the two neighbors a good chance to improve their strained
ties.
</P>
<P>
Greece has since softened its opposition to Turkey's eventual
membership in the EU. On Monday, Greece and Germany agreed to find
ways to help Turkey become a possible candidate country for the EU
by the Helsinki summit in December. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
