<HEADLINE> Radical Reform Of New Car Pricing In UK Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Competition Commission
Tuesday recommended radical reforms of the way new cars are sold
and distributed in Britain.
</P>
<P>
Details of the proposed reforms have been sent to leading
carmakers and consumer groups as part of an on-going investigation
into the new car market, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
Publication of the proposed reforms follows a mounting furor
over new car prices. According to the Consumers' Association,
carmakers charge up to 40 percent more for identical models in
Britain than in other parts of Europe.
</P>
<P>
The so-called "remedies letter" calls for changes in
recommended retail prices set by manufacturers for new cars.
</P>
<P>
The commission also called for an end to the "bundling" of
sales packages in which new cars are sold with incentives
including free insurance or roadside main tenance cover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
