<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SADC to Introduce Road Manifest to Regulate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Southern African Development
Community (SADC) members have decided to introduce a "road
manifest" to discipline regional trade.
</P>
<P>
The decision was made here Tuesday during a meeting of customs
directors from Malawi, Mozambique, South Africa, Swaziland,
Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference after the meeting, Director of
Mozambique' s Customs Restructuring Technical Unit (UTRA) Pedro
Bule said that the road manifest has not yet been introduced in
his country.
</P>
<P>
The manifest consists of a listing (at the origin of the
merchandise) of all items of cargo carried across one or more
countries.
</P>
<P>
Introducing this document in the region is a matter of urgency,
and the customs services expect their respective governments to
produce their points of view by next week, Bule said.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting discussed ways in which countries should
harmonize the implementation of both the road manifest and the
"customs assurance" of all merchandises on transit.
</P>
<P>
It also identified tax evasion and smuggling as a common
problem in the region, saying that a common strategy operated
under harmonized working mechanisms is needed to fight these
crimes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
