<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0055 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China on Decolonization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- To reach the goal of
decolonization laid down in relevant U.N. resolutions remains an
arduous and pressing task facing all member states and calls for
even greater efforts by the administering powers as well as the
whole international community, China said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Special Political and Decolonization Committee
of the 54th Session of the General Assembly, Chinese Deputy
Permanent Representative to the United Nations Shen Guofang said
that despite the profound changes in the international arena, the
relevant principles in the Charter of the United Nations and the
Declaration on the Granting of Independence to Colonial Countries
and Peoples are still of practical relevance today.
</P>
<P>
According to the charter, the declaration and relevant
resolutions of the United Nations General Assembly, the people of
non-self-governing territories enjoy the inalienable right to free
determination of their future status, Shen said.
</P>
<P>
It takes the joint efforts of all parties concerned, including
the United Nations, the people of non-self-governing territories
and the administering powers to ensure the exercise of this right,
Shen said.
</P>
<P>
As effective means to make known the will and situation of the
people of non-self-governing territories, dissemination of
information on decolonization and regional seminars participated
by, among others, people from non-self-governing territories
should continue to be accorded adequate attention and active
cooperation from all parties, Shen said.
</P>
<P>
"We call on the administering powers to cooperate more closely
with the U.N. and make sure that people of non-self-governing
territories fully understand their rights. Besides, administering
powers should also offer non-self-governing territories more
assistance to help them establish a sound economic base," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
