<HEADLINE> Thai Baht Firms as Bank of Thailand Intervenes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Thai baht strengthened over
the 40 per dollar level for the first time since September 16 on
Tuesday as the Bank of Thailand (BOT) tightened criteria for loans
to offshore companies.
</P>
<P>
BOT announced Tuesday that it has imposed a ceiling of 50
million baht (1.25 million U.S. dollars) for the loan to be
provided by any onshore company to a single offshore counterpart
to prevent speculative attacking on the baht.
</P>
<P>
The measure shored up the Thai baht value from under 40 baht
against the dollar to 39.81 baht in Tuesday afternoon's trading.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the announcement implied that there would be
greater restriction on bank outflows from onshore markets to
offshore markets.
</P>
<P>
Last week the baht dived to a 13-month low of 41.7 per dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
