<HEADLINE> U.S. Telecom Merger at 129 Billion Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 5 (Xinhua) -- In a single largest corporate
takeover, MCI WorldCom and Sprint announced Tuesday that they
reached a definitive merger agreement with a total value at 129
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The deal combines MCI WorldCom, the second largest U.S.
telephone company and Sprint, the third largest in a bid to take
on AT&AMP;T, the number one U.S. long-distance and wireless company.
</P>
<P>
The 129 billion dollar price tag includes the equity portion of
the long-distance business of Sprint as well as its PCS Group
subsidiary, which trades as a separate tracking stock.
</P>
<P>
MCI WorldCom's offer surpassed an earlier bid of 100 billion
dollars from regional BellSouth Corp which provides local phone
services in nine southeastern U.S. states but lacks a nationwide
wireless network.
</P>
<P>
The two companies expect the deal to be completed in the first
half of 2000 though analysts say the merger case would undergo
intense regulatory scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
The union of the two would control some 30 percent of the 80
billion dollar U.S. long-distance telephone market, compared with
48 percent for AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
MCI WorldCom and Sprint combined have more than 50 billion
dollars in annual sales against 53 billion dollars in sales for
AT&AMP;T in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
