<HEADLINE> EDS-More Added Chinese Technology Fair In Southern City (More Added) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Today was the opening day of a
five-day state-level fair on modern technology developments in the
southern city of Shenzhen, China's first.
</P>
<P>
In a speech at the opening ceremony tonight, Premier Zhu Rongji
said that the Chinese Government has decided to hold the event in
Shenzhen annually for better economic and technological
cooperation with other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has never faced such fierce challenges
internationally in technology as it has today, with the global
economy depending more on technology developments and the
industrial use of scientific research results and that he hopes
that Chinese enterprises and research institutes develop more hi-
tech goods for the international market.
</P>
<P>
China faces the urgent task of developing its economy by
relying on technological advancement, he said, adding that the
central authorities have promulgated a series of incentives and
policies to spur the development of new and high technology.
</P>
<P>
The fair is being sponsored by the Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation, Ministry of Science and Technology,
Ministry of Information Industry, Chinese Academy of Sciences, and
the Shenzhen municipal government, with the hope of speeding up
the industrial use of scientific research.
</P>
<P>
There will be an exhibit of computer and communications
products for use on the web, as well as forums. Some 15,000 new
research developments in electronic information, pharmaceuticals,
new materials, and bio-engineering will be on display.
</P>
<P>
The forums will discuss the present situation and future hi-
tech industrial trends, the information-based economy, state
development strategy, and related financial, stock and investment
sectors. Keynote speakers include major government officials,
economists, Nobel Prize winners, and scientists.
</P>
<P>
There are delegates from all Chinese provinces, autonomous
regions, and municipalities, and from 27 academies outside China,
and from the United States, Germany, Japan, Britain, and more than
20 other countries.
</P>
<P>
Some 50 multinationals are taking part and view it as a major
business event. The big names include Lucent, IBM, Siemens Nortel,
Ericsson, Epson, and Canon. 
</P>
