<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Cabinet Okays Tax Cut on Diesel for 3 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Thai cabinet Tuesday
approved a tax cut on diesel by 0.5 baht (1.25 U.S. cents) per
liter for three months for fear that higher oil prices will affect
the country's economic recovery, a Government House press release
said.
</P>
<P>
The move is part of a plan to ease the impact of higher
domestic oil prices and prevent effect on the economic growth in
the last quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
The cut, which will be effective from Wednesday to January 5,
2000, is expected to cost the government 2 billion baht (50
million dollars) in revenue and the government would have to raise
other taxes to make up for the losses.
</P>
<P>
The planned tax cut would include 0.42 baht in excise tax and 8
satang in local maintenance tax.
</P>
<P>
The government currently charges 2.308 baht per liter of diesel
and earns about 60.5 billion baht (1.5 billion dollars) from
gasoline and diesel taxes annually.
</P>
<P>
However, the tax on gasoline will not be lowered this time
since the price of gasoline is considered as having less direct
impact on the economy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the cabinet also reviewed the possible impact of
increased oil prices on the economy in the last three months of
this year.
</P>
<P>
The oil price hike will lead to an increase in commodity prices
and a decline in private consumption, the press release said.
</P>
<P>
Higher oil prices will also have a negative impact on Thai
exports as they will undermine the competitiveness of Thai
products by raising the production costs and will affect the world
economy, resulting in a drop of demand for Thai products.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet thus called for all sectors to take measures to
save energy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
