<HEADLINE> Thailand Sees Higher CPI in First 9 Months of 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Average consumer price index
(CPI) in the first nine months of this year in Thailand stood at
128, 0.4 percent higher compared with 127.5 in the same period of
last year, a Government House press release said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The CPI rose because of higher prices for clothing, water
supply, medical treatment, medicines, construction, vehicles,
tobacco and alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
However, CPI of food and beverage decreased in the same period
by 0.4 percent due to the lower prices of fragrant rice,
vegetables and fruits, vegetable oil and nutritious beverages.
</P>
<P>
CPI in September stood at 128.2 compared with 128 in August
because of higher prices for gasoline and water supply, according
to the press release. 
</P>
