<HEADLINE> Sino-DPRK Ties Hailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese People's Association
for Friendship with Foreign Countries (CPAFFC) held a reception
here today to mark the 50th anniversary of the establishment of
diplomatic ties between China and the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
CPAFFC President Qi Huaiyuan said that the Workers' Party of
Korea led by President Kim Il Sung and the DPRK recognized the
People's Republic of China (PRC) shortly after it was founded on
October 1 of 1949, and forged diplomatic ties with it on October 6.
This was an important event in bilateral ties, and ushered in a
new chapter of friendly ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
He added that the two countries have supported each other and
moved forward together over the past five decades.
</P>
<P>
Qi said that the two countries are linked by mountains and
rivers, adding that Sino-DPRK friendship initiated and fostered by
the elder generations of leaders has stood the test of time, and
has been deeply rooted in the hearts of both peoples.
</P>
<P>
Consolidating and developing traditional Sino-DPRK friendship
is a firm policy of the Chinese Government and sincere aspiration
of the Chinese people, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Pak Dong Chun, deputy foreign minister of the DPRK, who is here
to attend activities marking the 50th anniversary of bilateral
diplomatic ties, expressed the conviction that with joint efforts
of the two countries, Sino-DPRK friendship will continue to grow
in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
He said that the DPRK people are very happy to see the
achievements scored by the Chinese people over the past half-
century, and also wished that the Chinese people will achieve more
successes in the coming years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: World Community Attaches Importance to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The 54th General Assembly
session Monday kicked off the two-day plenary meeting on the
challenge of the rapid increase of ageing population in the world
at large, mirroring the global community is paying growing
attention to this issue.
</P>
<P>
Many government representatives, who took the floor at the
plenary session, agreed that the United Nations, the biggest
inter-government organization in today's world, should take more
effective steps to ensure that older persons enjoy a better quality
of life.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, taking the shape of an open debate, is seen as an
activity to enhance the public awareness to the pressing issue in
the world.
</P>
<P>
With the development in economy, science and technology,
education, culture and health care, and the improved life quality,
many countries, including China, are seeing the average life
expectancy of their population on the rise.
</P>
<P>
Although it is not news to anyone that our societies are
ageing, it is necessary to put some basic facts into sharper
focus. Globally, one out of every 10 persons is aged 60 or over;
by 2020, the corresponding figure will be one out of every eight;
and by 2150, every third person will be over 60.
</P>
<P>
"Although statistics are often said to hide more than they
reveal, these are by any standards startling numbers," U.N. Deputy
Secretary-General Louise Frechette told the plenary session
Monday.
</P>
<P>
"They show beyond any doubt that, even if all other things
remain equal, families, communities and societies will be
dramatically different a century from now," she said.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the 47th General Assembly session proclaimed 1999 as
the International Year of Older Persons, with its theme "Towards a
Society for All Ages." The decision, coupled with the U.N.
principles on ageing, showed the world body gave top priority to
the global issue of elderly persons.
</P>
<P>
The theme "is founded on the basic idea of inclusiveness, which
should inform human relations, family cohesion and social
development that strengthen the society," said General Assembly
President Theo-Ben Gurirab, who is the foreign minister of Namibia.
</P>
<P>
"In this sense, the theme of ageing links us to an early period
of the evolution of the society and community interdependence when
older persons were revered for their wisdom and as repositories of
traditions, customs and past achievements," he said.
</P>
<P>
Questions relating to ageing were on the U.N. agenda as far
back as 1948. The noble ideals and objectives enshrined in the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights enjoin the international
community to strive towards creating and maintaining human
societies based on family values of loving and caring among all
members of the family.
</P>
<P>
The International Year of Older Persons organized conferences,
seminars, research studies, and initiatives that explored and
promoted the theme.
</P>
<P>
"Promotional events are also abundant, including cultural,
educational, art and social activities, as well as the launching
of commemorative stamps, posters, and calendars with the Year's
logo," U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the International Year, the relevant activities have
so far involved 99 national committees and innumerable other
actors from all sectors -- governments, non-governmental
organizations, academic institutions and the corporate world, not
to mention the U.N. family.
</P>
<P>
From Bangladesh to Brazil, from China to Cameroon, all pursuit
the same goal: highlighting the issue of ageing and raising
individuals and societies all over the world.
</P>
<P>
"China conducted a nationwide publicity drive on respecting
older persons and held regional workshops on family support and
community service and a large performance on the life of older
persons, with proceeds allocated to older persons in poverty,"
Annan said in his latest report on ageing to the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
However, a huge elderly population and rapid speed of growth of
elderly population will surely pose a severe challenge to
developing countries, such as China, whose economies are still not
very developed.
</P>
<P>
Many developing countries are being marginalized in the
globalization process, and the ageing of the population will
become a major and more complicated social issue in the new
millennium. Therefore, the United Nations has the responsibility
to strengthen the relevant agencies and make their work more
effective to help, through various programs, the elderly
population enjoy their life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
