<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fed Leaves Interest Rates Unchanged for the Present </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal Reserve
decided Tuesday not to raise interest rates but left open the
possibility of a third rate increase later this year.
</P>
<P>
The Fed policy-makers moved their policy directive, which
signals the future course of interest rates, from neutral to one
tilting toward a rate increase.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's action was announced by the Federal Open Market
Committee in a brief statement after its closed-door meeting.
</P>
<P>
By leaving interest rates unchanged, the federal funds rate,
the interest that banks charge each other on overnight loans,
continues to stand at 5.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
Today's decision to leave rates unchanged had been widely
expected. For the second time this year, the Fed opted not to
raise rates while announcing a switch in its policy directive from
a neutral stance to one leaning toward a rate increase in the
future.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Fed said "the growth of demand has continued
to outpace that of supply as evidenced by a decreasing pool of
available workers willing to take jobs. In these circumstances,
the Federal Open Market Committee will need to be especially alert
in the months ahead to the potential for costs to increase
significantly... in a manner that could contribute to inflation
pressures and undermine the impressive performance of the
economy."
</P>
<P>
The brief statement emphasized that the switch did not signal
an imminent increase. A decision to raise rates in the future
would be based on upcoming economic data on growth and inflation,
the policy-makers said.
</P>
<P>
Many analysts believed the Fed would leave rates unchanged
because inflation had remained well-behaved despite strong
economic growth and an unemployment rate remaining at a 29-year
low.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many economists said growth slowing in the second
quarter to 1.6 percent annual rate was a temporary lull. They are
looking for a growth rate of 4 percent in both the third and
fourth quarters, far above the 3 percent rate many Fed
policy-makers believe is prudent with today's tight labor market.
So they believe the Fed may raise rates this year by a quarter of
a point when it meets on Nov. 16, depending on what a fresh round
of economic data released between now and then.
</P>
<P>
The Fed already raised the federal funds rates twice early this
year by the same amount of one quarter point. 
</P>
</TEXT>
