<HEADLINE> China Calls on Countries to Pay U.N. Dues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- China Tuesday called on
some Member State to honor the principle of the U.N. Charter and
legal obligation by paying their U.N. dues in full, on time and
without conditions.
</P>
<P>
Shen Guofang, China's deputy permanent representative to the
United Nations, made the statement at the Fifth Committee of the
General Assembly, when it met in a plenary session to discuss the
financial situation of the world body.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that all Member States can honor the financial
obligation to the United Nations under the Charter, and the
largest debtor in particular will do something meaningful to pay
their dues in full, on time and without condition," he said.
</P>
<P>
The delayment in paying their dues is the main factor which has
plunged the United Nations into chronic financial crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
A certain big country failed to pay its U.N. arrears not
because of its economic difficulties, but because of political
purposes, or because of the party struggle within the country,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is unacceptable that some country fails to honor the
principle of the U.N. Charter and the legal obligations, and
imposes pressure on other U.N. members by delaying its payment,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
China is very much concerned about the fact that the financial
crisis has largely affected the implementation of some programs
at the United Nations, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
