<HEADLINE> Moratorium Expected on Disputed Fishing in New Brunswick </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Fishing dispute over the catch of
Atlantic lobsters has entered its third day with a moratorium
expected to calm the conflicting natives and non-natives in
troubled New Brunswick, Canada.
</P>
<P>
Fisheries Minister Herb Dhaliwal said Tuesday that he was
pleased with native efforts to defuse the situation.
</P>
<P>
Atlantic Mi'kmaq chiefs are reported to meet Tuesday on a
30-day fishing moratorium in Halifax, Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
Tensions have remained high in the Atlantic province of Canada
following a Supreme Court ruling last month that allows natives to
fish out of season and without a license to earn a moderate
livelihood.
</P>
<P>
While the glimmer of hope is expected to loom large, local
media have reported continued tension over the fishing rights.
</P>
<P>
A vacant cottage outside a native Mi'kmaq reserve in the
province was set ablaze late Monday. Police indicated the fire was
deliberately set against non-natives, but they fell short of
saying who were suspects.
</P>
<P>
Natives also feel frustrated that no charges have been laid
after three aboriginal men were injured Sunday night, when their
truck collided with a vehicle driven by non-natives.
</P>
<P>
The young natives were beaten after the collision, local media
said.
</P>
<P>
There have been fears about the spreading of the conflicts into
other Atlantic provinces.
</P>
<P>
About 200 Prince Edward Island lobster fishermen demonstrated
Tuesday morning at the Department of Fisheries office in
Charlottetown.
</P>
<P>
In Nova Scotia, non-natives have set a deadline until 6 p.m.
Tuesday for the federal government to curb the lobster fishing by
natives.
</P>
<P>
Non-native fishermen are worrying that lobster stocks could be
depleted before they are allowed to open fishery next spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
