<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa-EU Trade Deal Under Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Renewed wrangling over
wines and spirits is threatening to unravel the long-awaited
trade, development and cooperation deal between the European Union
and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Four years in the making, the deal is due to be signed soon in
Pretoria. Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, who is also the EU
president, is scheduled to attend the signing ceremony, government
sources said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Officials from both sides were feverishly working to overcome
differences on the fine print of crucial areas of the draft
agreement. They center on the wines and spirits agreement which
forms part of the overall pact.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the EU was attempting to get South Africa to
relinquish not only the names "port" and "sherry" but further
"traditional expressions". These include classification details
like ruby or tawny for port and wine.
</P>
<P>
Agreement in principle on the wines and spirits, the last
remaining hurdle in the overall accord, was reached earlier this
year by politicians from both sides. Officials were left to
negotiate the fine print.
</P>
<P>
An EU diplomat said the latest disagreements were the result of
pressure on the South African government by the local wine and
spirits industry.
</P>
<P>
But South African sources said the earlier political agreement
had left too many gaps and they were now difficult to close.
</P>
<P>
The EU's stance is seen by many observers as part of a larger
campaign to protect geographical and other denominations for wines
and foodstuffs on a global scale. It is understood that the
United States is paying close attention to the EU-S. African
negotiations because of the possibility that international
precedents may be set.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the United States had warned South Africa that it
could take action against Pretoria if the latter caved in to EU
demands.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural department negotiator Ben van Wyk said his
country felt that some of the EU demand should be resolved at a
multilateral level.
</P>
<P>
Talks had been suspended pending further consultations between
the negotiators and their principals, he said.
</P>
<P>
Coreper, the EU ambassadors' body, meets Wednesday to consider,
among other things, a signing ceremony next Monday minus the wines
and spirits components of the overall agreement. This would allow
officials to continue negotiations on the remaining sticking
points.
</P>
<P>
Should these negotiations continue beyond next January, South
Africa's wine and spirits producers would not benefit from reduced
tariffs.
</P>
<P>
January 1 is the implementation date for the crucial trade
component of the EU-S. African deal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
