<HEADLINE> Nigeria, S. Africa Committed to Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria and South Africa Tuesday
reached wide ranging agreement on mutual cooperation at the end of
an inaugural session of the Nigeria-South Africa Commission in
Abuja, Nigeria's capital.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, attended by vice-presidents of both
countries, focused on the healthy development of the economic
ties, cooperation in infrastructure, and the Joint Commission
which has just been launched between the two most important
countries in sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
A communique issued at the end of the meeting said the economic
 cooperation between the two countries will center on the areas of
cement, automotive, pulp and paper, food processing, fertilizers
and sugar production.
</P>
<P>
The two nations also agreed to exploit last year's memorandum
of understanding between the two nations by "following up"
cooperation in geology exploration, mining technology,
metallurgical and mineral processing, mineral promotion and
development.
</P>
<P>
Both countries agreed to establish a working group of technical
experts to plan, implement and monitor strategies for cooperation
in the exploration and production of crude oil.
</P>
<P>
Under the latest sales arrangement released last month by the
state- owned Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation, South Africa
would start buying oil from Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
At the conclusion of Tuesday's meeting, both countries agreed
to collaborate in "data acquisition and management" of the solid
minerals development.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries went sour during the reign
of the late Nigerian military dictator General Sani Abacha.
</P>
<P>
But "Nigeria and South African must rapidly put their troubled
histories behind them and start fulfilling the greatest destinies
thrust on them by nature for the good of their citizens and the
rest of Africa," Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo said Monday
when meeting South African Vice President Jacob Zuma.
</P>
<P>
He said that with democratization and the restoration of
majority rule in Nigeria, the two countries had incentives for
increased cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The next meeting of the Nigeria-South Africa Joint Commission
will be held in South Africa six months later. 
</P>
</TEXT>
