<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's New PM, Power of Privatization Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Atef Obeid, Egypt's new prime
minister named on Tuesday by President Hosni Mubarak, is an
economic expert who was the power of the country's economic
reforms featured in privatization.
</P>
<P>
Obeid was born on April 14, 1932 in the Nile Delta city of
Tanta, capital of Gharbia Governorate, 80 kilometers north of
Cairo.
</P>
<P>
He graduated from the Faculty of Commerce of Cairo University
in 1952 with a bachelor's degree and became an assistant professor
at Ain Shams University.
</P>
<P>
After receiving a doctorate in business administration from
Illinois University in the United States in 1962, Obeid taught at
Cairo University's faculty of commerce. From 1978 to 1984, he was
the head of the university's business administration department.
</P>
<P>
He also worked as a part-time professor at the American
University in Cairo between 1965 and 1984. He became an adviser
for the ministries of electricity, industry, higher education,
housing and information in 1973-84.
</P>
<P>
In 1984, Obeid assumed the post of minister of state for
administration development and later minister of cabinet affairs
in charge of environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
In October 1993, he was appointed as public business sector
minister, which he held until he was named prime minister on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Before becoming public sector minister, Obeid took part in the
preparations of a program, sponsored by the International Monetary
Fund and the World Bank, for Egyptian economic reforms, which
began in 1991.
</P>
<P>
Under the privatization program which kicked off in 1995, Egypt
planned to sell 314 state-owned firms. So far, the government has
sold part of 123 firms, or about 39 percent of the total
government-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
In August, Egypt's Middle East News Agency said the government
earned 9.22 billion Egyptian pounds (2.67 billion U.S. dollars) by
privatizing the state-owned firms.
</P>
<P>
Obeid is married and has a son, Walid, and a daughter, Nora.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
