<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Tuesday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak was sworn in on
Tuesday for a fourth six-year term.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak took the constitutional oath for the office at an
extraordinary session of the parliament, the Peoples' Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The president was re-elected on September 26 by winning about
94 percent "yes" votes in a yes-or-no, uncontested referendum.
(BC-Egypt-President-Swearing-in)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israel and the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) signed here Tuesday an agreement on opening the safe passage
linking the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, reached Monday night and approved later by both
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat,
was inked by PNA Civil Affairs Minister Jamil Tarif and Israeli
Public Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami.
</P>
<P>
The agreement stipulates that all Palestinians and foreign
visitors to the Gaza Strip and the West Bank areas will be allowed
to travel between the two Palestinian territories within the
framework of the safe passage. (BC-Israel-Safe Passage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on Tuesday accepted
the resignation of the cabinet submitted by Prime Minister Kamal
El-Ganzouri.
</P>
<P>
Under Egypt's constitution, the cabinet must resign to pave the
way for a new cabinet in the wake of a new presidential term in
office. (BC-Egypt-Cabinet-Resignation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli and Palestinian negotiators Tuesday hailed
a newly-clinched deal on the first-ever safe passage route between
Gaza and the West Bank as an important step for the revived peace
process.
</P>
<P>
"It is in our interest to have the Palestinian population in a
state of economic and cultural satisfaction," Israeli Internal
Security Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami told reporters after signing a
protocol on the safe passage route with Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Minister of Civilian Affairs Jamal Tarif.
(BC-Israel-Palestinians-Safe Passage)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak on Tuesday appointed
Atef Ebeid, minister of public business sector, as the new prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Ebeid, Mubarak asked him to form a new
government, the country's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Ebeid told reporters after the meeting that he was given the
directives as the criteria for choosing the cabinet ministers and
that he will submit to the president a list of the ministers on
Saturday. (BC-Egypt-PM-Appointment) 
</P>
