<HEADLINE> IMF: Thailand's Economic Recovery Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's economic recovery
is now underway and the 1999 growth is expected to reach 3-4
percent, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) announced on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
IMF's executive board approved Tuesday the completion of the
eighth review under Thailand's Stand-By Arrangement, allowing the
Thai authorities to draw a further 500 million U.S. dollars from
the financial bailout package.
</P>
<P>
However, in view of the gathering recovery and stronger
external position, the Thai government announced last month that
it does not intend to use these additional resources.
</P>
<P>
To date, Thailand has drawn 14.1 billion dollars from bilateral
and multilateral contributors to its financing package totaling
172 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
"Directors welcomed the marked improvement in Thailand's
economic prospects," IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus said
in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"They (directors) noted that the recovery is now underway with
growing signs of a rebound in manufacturing, exports, and domestic
consumption prompting an upward revision in the 1999 growth
forecast to 3-4 percent," he said.
</P>
<P>
"To consolidate this process, which is at an early stage,
directors stressed the importance of maintaining supportive
macroeconomic policies and accelerating corporate and financial
reforms," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
