<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka's Tea Crop Declines Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's tea crop of August
declined sharply to 19.4 million kilograms, the lowest for the
month since 1995, tea brokers said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Forbes &AMP; Walker Tea Brokers Ltd. said in its latest market
report that the figure for August shows a decline of 7.1 million
kilograms or 26.5 percent against the corresponding figure of 26.5
million kilograms for the same month of last year.
</P>
<P>
During the cumulative period from January to August this year,
the total production of 184.2 million kilograms is 1 million
kilograms lower than the corresponding figure of last year.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the cumulative figure shows a decline
compared with the preceding year's figure for the first time this
year.
</P>
<P>
Tea exports during the month of August recorded an increase of
about 1.38 million kilograms over a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
However, total tea exports from January to August this year was
178.2 million kilograms, still 1.5 million kilograms lower than
last year, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka has been the main producer and exporter of tea in the
world. Last year it recorded the largest-ever crop of 280 million
kilograms and exported 269.6 million kilograms to the Commonwealth
of Independent States, the United Arab Emirates, Turkey and other
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
