<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Visitors Continue To Stream Into China's Terra Cotta Warrior Museum </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The museum housing thousands of
terra cotta warriors and horses that were buried along with the
Chinese emperor Qin Shihuang has had more than 40 million visitors
since it opened to the public 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The museum, 37 kilometers east of Xi'an, the capital of
northwestern China's Shaanxi Province, celebrated its 20th
anniversary today and opened a new hall for other relics unearthed
from the imperial tomb.
</P>
<P>
There have been more than 100 heads of state among those
visitors, according to the museum's curator, Wu Yongqi. The museum
houses over 7,000 life-sized terra cotta warriors and horses
unearthed since 1974, and tens of thousands of weapons. The relics
hall displays bronze chariots, a bronze cooking vessel weighing
212 kilograms, and an exhibition depicting the museum's 20-year
history. Wu says that some relics that haven't been previously
shown will be on display in the hall.
</P>
<P>
The Shaanxi government is working on plans to expand the museum,
according to vice-governor Zhao Dequan.
</P>
<P>
The lifelike soldiers and horses have been referred to as the
8th wonder of the world. They were made over 2,200 years ago
during the Qin Dynasty (221 BC -- 207 BC) and were buried less
than a mile from the emperor's tomb to protect his glory in the
afterlife. This "most splendid archeological find" of the century
was discovered accidentally in 1974 by a farmer who was digging a
well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
