<HEADLINE> Forum of Federations Opens in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A high-level international
conference on federalism opened Wednesday in Mont-Tremblant of
Canada's Quebec province.
</P>
<P>
Opening the three-day Forum of Federations attended by some 500
politicians and academics from 25 countries, Canadian Prime
Minister Jean Chretien hailed the first gathering for discussions
on federalism since the forum was established 200 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister termed the essence of federalism as "balance
" between different identities, saying "Canadian federalism is
based on sharing and solidarity."
</P>
<P>
Visiting Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo made the keynote
address to the conference on his country's experience and
achievements in practicing federalism.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton is expected at the closing of the
conference Friday, when he will pay a 22-hour visit to Canada.
</P>
<P>
Canadian media said that the 3 million-dollar (2.1 million U.S.
dollar) conference was chiefly sponsored by the federal government.
Participants will compare notes on their versions of federation
and work toward a secretariat for the forum. 
</P>
