<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior U.S. Politicians Urge Delay in Vote on Nuclear Test Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Three former senior U.S.
administration officials Wednesday urged the Senate to delay the
vote until next session of Congress on a treaty that would ban all
nuclear weapons tests.
</P>
<P>
The call was made by John Deutch, former deputy secretary of
defense and former director of the Central Intelligence Agency (
CIA), Henry Kissinger, former secretary of state, and Brent
Scowcroft, former national security adviser.
</P>
<P>
In a joint opinion article in The Washington Post, they said
the treaty's supporters and opponents are "both wrong."
</P>
<P>
The Senate is scheduled to vote October 12 on whether to ratify
the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT). The administration and
the Republicans both launched campaigns for and against the treaty.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton is expected to make an appeal for the
ratification of the treaty at a White House event later Wednesday
while the Republicans will give a press conference to oppose it
before the president.
</P>
<P>
"While we are no fans of the CTBT, our purpose here is not to
argue its merits and defects. Our point is more straight-forward.
The simple fact is that it is premature for the Senate to vote on
the CTBT -- at least," Deutch, Kissinger and Scowcroft said.
</P>
<P>
"If we act now, there could be real costs and risks to our
security interests, including our nonproliferation objectives,"
they noted.
</P>
<P>
They challenges the argument by the supporters that
ratification of the treaty will make a major contribution to
limiting the spread of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The treaty requires that each of 44 specific countries sign and
ratify the document before it enters into force. Only 23 of those
countries have done so thus far.
</P>
<P>
"The United States should take advantage of this situation to
delay a vote on ratification, without prejudice to eventual action
on the treaty," the article said.
</P>
<P>
"In light of the uncertainty, and in the absence of any
compelling reasons for early ratification, it is unwise to take
early ratification now that constrain this or future presidents'
choices about how best to pursue our nonproliferation and other
national security goals while maintaining the effectiveness and
credibility of our nuclear deterrent," it added.
</P>
<P>
"We urge the Senate leadership to reach an understanding with
the president to suspend action on the CTBT, at least for the
duration of the 106th Congress," it concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
