<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Takes Measures to Reduce Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government has
decided to stop importing diesel taxis after next year and will
provide grants to assist taxis owners to switch to liquid
petroleum gas (LPG) vehicles as a measure to improve the city's
air quality.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed here Wednesday by Tung Chee Hwa, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) in
his third policy address.
</P>
<P>
The government has proposed to the taxi trade that all diesel
taxis over seven years old be taken off the road by 2003 and that
no diesel taxis be allowed after 2006, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 30 percent of Hong Kong's existing fleet of half a
million vehicles are diesel-powered and diesel vehicles account
for nearly 70 percent of the total distance traveled on the roads.
</P>
<P>
As a result, diesel vehicles account for 98 percent of the
respirable particulates and 85 percent of the nitrogen oxide
emitted by vehicles.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the key to prevent and abate air pollution at
street level is to control the use of, improve and replace diesel
vehicles," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
As early as 1994, more stringent standards for new diesel
vehicles, known as Euro standards, were introduced in Hong Kong to
reduce air pollution.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are 18,000 diesel taxis, 6,000-odd diesel
light buses, 70,000 other diesel light vehicles, 50,000 of which
are of pre-Euro standards, in Hong Kong. On a trial basis,
particulate traps will be installed in these pre-Euro-standard
vehicles to reduce pollution.
</P>
<P>
There are also 12,000 diesel buses and almost 40,000 other
medium and heavy diesel vehicles in Hong Kong. Half of these buses
and over 60 percent of the medium and heavy diesel vehicles,
totaling some 30,000, are pre-Euro standard vehicles. Installing
catalytic converters is believed to be the best way to reduce
emissions from these old diesel vehicles.
</P>
<P>
A total of 1.4 billion HK dollars (179 million U.S. dollars)
has been set aside as grants to owners of taxis, light buses and
other pre-Euro standard diesel vehicles for the purpose of
switching over to LPG, installation of particulate traps and the
fitting of catalytic converters, the chief executive said.
</P>
<P>
In addition, there are other measures to reduce air pollution.
</P>
<P>
The Environmental Protection Department is expanding its smoky
vehicle spotter program and has been using more sophisticated
testing equipment for smoky vehicles since last month. Meanwhile,
the police have stepped up enforcement action against smoky
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
"We also intend to expand the pedestrian zones in crowded and
more polluted parts of our city so as to reduce pollution caused
by vehicle emissions," the chief executive said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bahraini Emir Arrives in UAE for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Bahraini Emir Sheikh Hamad Bin
Isa Al-Khalifa arrived here Wednesday for a visit to the United
Arab Emirates (UAE), Emirates News Agency (WAM) reported.
</P>
<P>
The emir was greeted at the airport by Abu Dhabi Crown Prince
and Deputy Supreme Commander of the UAE Armed Forces Sheikh
Khalifa Bin Zayed Al-Nahyan, Dubai Crown Prince and UAE Defense
Minister General Sheikh Mohammad Bin Rashid al-Maktoum and other
officials.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Hamad will meet UAE President Sheikh Zayed
Bin Sultan Al-Nahyan, WAM said, without giving further details.
</P>
<P>
The UAE and Bahrain are members of the regional political and
economic alliance, the Gulf Cooperation Council, which also
includes Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman and Qatar. 
</P>
