<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Unveils Statue to Mark Achievement in River Blindness Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
unveiled a statue of a boy leading a blind man at its headquarters
Wednesday to mark the impending elimination of onchocerciasis,
popularly known as river blindness, in West Africa.
</P>
<P>
The unveiling of the statue should stand for recognition of
what public and private sector partnerships can do and a beginning
of a new era in this field, said WHO Director-General Dr Gro
Harlem Brundtland at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to a landmark example of public and private-sector
collaboration, the transmission of the river blindness disease is
on the verge of elimination in West Africa.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 12 million children, who would have lived with the
risk of being blinded by onchocerciasis, have grown up without
that risk to be independent and productive adults, according to
WHO. On the 25 million hectares of land now reclaimed for
cultivation, enough food is produced to feed 17 million people per
year.
</P>
<P>
Present at the unveiling were former U.S. President Jimmy
Carter, Dutch Minister for Development Cooperation Eveline
Herfkens, World Bank President James Wolfensohn and the Chief
Executive Officer of Merck &AMP; Co, Inc, Ray Gilmartin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
