<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico Returns "Junk Choppers" to U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Mexico last month returned 72
U.S. Army helicopters of the Vietnam War-vintage to the United
States three years after they were donated to aid drug war, the U.
S. media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The helicopters were rejected as junk by a frustrated Mexican
military that never got more than a dozen of the clunkers airborne
at any one time, according to U.S. and Mexican officials. The
73rd helicopter had already been destroyed in a crash.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials agreed earlier this year to refurbish 20 of the
helicopters at U.S. expense at a cost of about 1.4 million U.S.
dollars per chopper.
</P>
<P>
But the Mexican military has told its U.S. counterparts it
still does not want them.
</P>
<P>
The UH-1H Huey helicopters were donated to Mexican authorities
to boost the Mexican military's efforts to combat drug production
and trafficking, improving the mobility of anti-drug squads over
rough terrain.
</P>
<P>
However, the entire fleet had been grounded since March 1998
when two Mexican Army crew members were killed in a crash because
of possibly faulty gearboxes in the choppers.
</P>
<P>
Mexico decided to return them because it does not believe it is
cost-effective for them to continue to fly them and ask the U.S.
military to take them back.
</P>
<P>
All the choppers were loaded into trucks and driven back to the
U.S. last month unceremoniously.
</P>
<P>
Three years ago, both Mexican and U.S. officials lauded the
donation as a symbol of cooperation in the war against drug
trafficking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0105 </DOCNO>
