<HEADLINE> HK Chief Executive Forecasts 2-Pct Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), expressed
the confidence here Wednesday that Hong Kong is expected to record
an economic growth rate of over 2 percent in the second half of
1999.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong economy has turned the corner and Hong Kong still
stands at the position close to the top level of the international
standard," said Tung at a press conference following the
publication of his third policy address.
</P>
<P>
Tung said the Hong Kong SAR government managed to stabilize the
financial market in the past two years and at the same time
introduced a series of relief measures, including reducing tax
rates and supporting small and medium-sized enterprises.
</P>
<P>
"All these efforts have begun to yield fruits and Hong Kong has
been benefiting from its efforts," said Tung.
</P>
<P>
He said Hong Kong must continue to improve itself to stay
competitive and must have long-term strategies, especially in the
areas of education and environment.
</P>
<P>
"Our objective is not only to make Hong Kong a world-class city,
but to enable Hong Kong's economy to continue to growth, to create
more job opportunities and also to make the community more
affluent," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the housing needs of the society, the chief
executive pledged to reduce the waiting time for public rental
housing to three years by March 2006, from the seven years when he
took office in 1997.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped to stabilize property prices and said Hong Kong
has already developed a land reserve to deal with the problem.
</P>
<P>
Tung said the continuous economic growth will improve
employment and such measures as developing tourism and small and
medium-sized enterprises and innovating technology have all been
taken for this target. 
</P>
</TEXT>
