<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Factory Orders Rise 1.3 Percent in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Commerce Department
reported Wednesday that orders to U.S. factories for manufactured
goods rose 1.3 percent in August, following a 2.5 percent gain in
July.
</P>
<P>
The unexpected increase was led by bigger demand for airplanes
and other transportation products and electronic equipment, the
department said.
</P>
<P>
August's performance marks the 12th increase in the last 15
months and provides fresh evidence of the continued rebound of the
manufacturing sector, which has been battered by a global
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The transportation sector posted the biggest increase, the
fourth monthly gain in a row, rising 4.8 percent in August. Demand
for airplane and aircraft parts led growth in this category. In
July, transportation orders rose 2.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
If excluding the volatile transportation category, factory
orders would have risen a solid 0.8 percent in August, the eighth
increase in the last 10 months.
</P>
<P>
Last month's orders for electronic and other electrical
equipment grew by 0.8 percent in August, following a big jump of 8
percent the month before.
</P>
<P>
The rise in overall factory orders occurred despite a 2.1
decrease in orders for industrial machinery and equipment, the
sector that includes computers. That drop followed a hefty 10.5
percent gain in July.
</P>
<P>
Orders for primary metals, the category that includes steel,
also fell 1.0 percent in August, after rising 3.4 percent the
month before.
</P>
<P>
Orders for durable goods rose 1.2 percent in August, following
a 4.3 percent gain in July. Meanwhile, orders for nondurable
goods, such as fuel, grew by 1.5 percent with orders for
petroleum, coal products, chemicals and paper registering the
biggest increases. In July, nondurable-goods orders picked up just
0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. manufacturing sector continues to recover from the
global economic crisis, which dampened overseas demand for U.S.
goods. At the same time, manufacturers faced competition from a
flood of cheaper imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, October 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON -- The number of people confirmed dead in the London
train crash has risen to 27, but police warned on Wednesday that
the death toll is likely to rise further.
</P>
<P>
The crash happened on Tuesday morning when the three-carriage
service run by Thames Trains from Paddington to Bedwyn in
Wiltshire collided with the London-bound Great Western 125 express
train from Cheltenham at Ladbroke Grove.
</P>
<P>
The initial Health and Safety Executive investigation suggests
the Thames train passed one red and two yellow warning signals,
ploughing into the Great Western which had been given a green
light.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Assistant Commissioner Andy Trotter, of the Metropolitan
Police, said the search for bodies would concentrate on the front
first-class carriage of the Great Western train, which was "
devastated" by fire.
</P>
<P>
The grisly search was suspended on Tuesday night with the
emergency services sure there was no one else left alive on either
train.
</P>
<P>
Of the 27 confirmed dead, 12 bodies remain at the scene but he
said he hoped they would all be removed by the end of Wednesday.
(Britain-Train Crash-Death Toll)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev said Wednesday that
Russian federal troops may cross the Terek River in Chechnya in
its latest campaign to root out Islamic rebels in the breakaway
republic.
</P>
<P>
"Everything will depend on the situation," he said, noting
that some of the Russian units have already advanced to as far as
Terek.
</P>
<P>
All federal troops have reached the Terokumsky irrigation
channel laid along Terek at a distance of 10 kilometers, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Terek River passes about 15 kilometers north of Grozny,
the regional capital.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev said that the federal grouping continues "to create a
security zone around the republic" in the first stage of the
operation.
</P>
<P>
He said federal forces, which had encountered "pocket
resistance" from the rebels, might face large-scale military
operations by Chechen formations.
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared for everything," he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia lost two warplanes, one Su-24 attack plane and a Su-24
bomber, earlier this week and the fate of the pilots remained
unknown.
</P>
<P>
Search and rescue operation continues to locate the pilots. "
We have not lost hope for saving them," the defense minister said.
(Russia-Chechnya-Fighting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- Indian Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee
Wednesday beat his Congress rival Karan Singh by 123,624 votes,
winning his seat in the Lucknow constituency in North India's
Uttar Pradesh state.
</P>
<P>
This was the fourth time he won the seat in Lucknow. He had won
the seat thrice in a row in 1991, 1996 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister expressed confidence here that the BJP-led
National Democratic Alliance will get a clear majority in the Lok
Sabha elections and that the results so far are in accordance with
its expectations.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether he was hopeful of becoming the prime minister
again, he merely smiled and said, "Let's see how the results come.
"
</P>
<P>
Thanking the Delhi voters for electing all the seven BJP
candidates, he said the capital has created history once more.
</P>
<P>
"The victory is significant though Delhi has returned such a
verdict in the past too," he added.
</P>
<P>
In the 1998 elections, the BJP won only one seat out of seven
in Delhi, but it made a clean sweep Wednesday by winning seven
seats and re-establishing its stronghold in the country's capital.
(India-Vajpayee-Poll Victory) 
</P>
</TEXT>
