<HEADLINE> Russian Regional Leader Urges Talks With Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Faced with a mounting pressure of
refugees from Chechnya, the leader of the Russian republic of
Ingushetia on Wednesday urged the federal government to start
talks with Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov.
</P>
<P>
"The federal center should begin intensive talks as soon as
possible with the Chechen leadership represented by Maskhadov,"
Ingush President Ruslan Aushev said at a meeting chaired by
Russian Deputy Prime Minister Valentina Matviyenko in Magas.
</P>
<P>
Ingush leaders oppose the use of force in resolving the
Chechen problem, although terrorism must be thwarted, he said. "
We must turn the Chechen people into an ally in combating
terrorism," the Interfax news agency quoted Aushev as saying.
</P>
<P>
Aushev warned against repeating the mistakes of the 1996 war,
which cost 90,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
Ingushetia, already hosting 128,000 Chechen refugees, might
see the total number rising to 270,000-300,000 if a large-scale
land campaign starts. The tiny republic, which has a population
of about 300,000, will be even more hard-pressed to appeal for
outside help.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister Matviyenko, who is in charge of social
affairs, arrived in Ingushetia to oversee the refugee problem.
She told reporters that Russia can cope with the refugee problem
by itself and does not need international help at the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
