<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Apache Company Buys Shell Canada's Oil Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. energy giant Apache Corp. is
buying Shell Canada Ltd.'s conventional oil business unit at 770
million Canadian dollars (about 524 million U.S. dollars), the
Canadian newspaper Globe and Mail reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two companies announced Tuesday that the deal could be
closed next month to add the acquisition of Shell's Plain unit to
the U.S. firm, boosting its oil production almost fivefold in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
It means that Apache, whose current Canadian output is a modest
2,700 barrels per day, will become one of the top 25 oil producers
in Canada.
</P>
<P>
Apache President Steven Farris described the deal as a "
strategic step," which will bring Canadian properties to 19
percent of the company's total proven reserves.
</P>
<P>
In its first major foray in 1995, Apache took over Calgary-
based Dekalb Energy Co. for 285 million Canadian dollars (about
194 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
With a stock market value of about 4.5 billion U.S. dollars,
Apache expects Shell's Plain unit to keep its capacity of
producing almost 13,400 barrels of oil a day plus a daily 45
million cubic feet of natural gas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
