<HEADLINE> Dutch Banks Open Long-term Credits for Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 6 (Xinhua ) -- Two Dutch banks have opened two
8.5-year credit lines totaling dlrs 2 billion for the iranian
investors, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Khosrow Salour, the commercial advisor to the Embassy of the
Netherlands in Iran, on Tuesday told the agency that the credit
lines are separate form the investments Dutch companies have so
far poured into the Iranian oil, gas, copper and petrochemical
sectors.
</P>
<P>
He put the volume of Iran-Holland trade for 1998 at about dlrs
706 million, adding that Iran's exports to the Netherlands amounted
to dlrs 413.5 million, 90 percent of which were crude oil.
</P>
<P>
Salour said that while crude oil constituted the main Iranian
export item to the Netherlands, industrial machinery, tire and
textile industries, steel, oil equipment and petrochemical
substances were major exports of that country to Iran.
</P>
<P>
He said that given the growing trend of economic cooperation
between the two countries, Dutch officials are negotiating with
authorities of the Iranian economy and finance ministry to
finalize new agreements for investments in Iran. 
</P>
