<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister, Top DPRK Lawmaker Discuss Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chinese Foreign
Minister Tang Jiaxuan on Wednesday held talks with Kim Yong Nam,
President of the Supreme People's Assembly of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), to discuss relations between
their two countries.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Tang said that the Chinese-Korean
friendship has stood the test of changes in international
situation since the two countries established diplomatic relations
half a century ago.
</P>
<P>
He said that Kim's successful visit to China in June helped
consolidate and develop the Chinese-Korean friendship.
</P>
<P>
Tang, who arrived here Tuesday for an official goodwill visit,
also expressed the belief that this traditional friendship will be
more fruitful in the next century with the kind care of their
leaders and the concerted efforts by both sides.
</P>
<P>
Describing the establishment of diplomatic ties between China
and the DPRK as "a major event," Kim said that Korean-Chinese
relations are witnessing further development with the care from
King Jong Il, General Secretary of the Workers' Party of Korea,
and Jiang Zemin, Chinese President and General Secretary of the
Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
He added that Tang's current visit will help further such
friendly ties.
</P>
<P>
Macao's upcoming return to China will further prove the
correctness of China's policy to reunify the country, and the DPRK
is strongly opposed to the "two-state" statements made by Lee Teng-
hui, leader of the Taiwanese authorities, he said.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday night, Tang and his DPRK counterpart, Baek Nam Sun,
attended a banquet hosted by the DPRK Foreign Ministry to
celebrate the 50th anniversary of the founding of diplomatic ties
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, Tang called on Kim Yang Gon, director of the
International Affairs Department of the Central Committee of the
Workers' Party. He also met Baek Nam Sun on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
China and the DPRK established diplomatic relations on October
6, 1949. 
