<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rios Advances into Quarterfinals at Shanghai Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Top seed Marcelo Rios and "
lucky loser" Todd Woodbridge have won through to play each other
in the quarterfinals of the Heineken Open, Shanghai after they
scored vastly different types of victories here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Under cloudy and at times threatening skies, 23-year-old Rios
comfortably moved past Croatian Ivan Ljubicic 6-3, 6-2 while
Woodbridge rallied from a match point down to beat Hyung-Taik Lee
of South Korea 5-7, 6-2, 7-6 (10-8).
</P>
<P>
Woodbridge had ironically lost to the South Korean in the last
round of qualifying but got into the main draw when his doubles
partner Mark Woodforde withdrew because of an arm injury.
</P>
<P>
Rios declared that he can feel his confidence slowly returning
and with each match he plays better. The world number seven said
his left leg injury which kept him out of ATP Tour events in the
middle of the year, including Wimbledon, was responding well to
continuous treatment.
</P>
<P>
"When you are not injured it's pretty easy to play well, when
you have problems with your body, it's pretty hard to go on court,
" said Rios.
</P>
<P>
Woodbridge put things together very well against Lee and said
it was one of the best matches he had played for a very long time.
</P>
<P>
He added that if he plays well he should not have trouble with
Woodbridge because "he's a doubles player now". Amusingly, barely
an hour earlier Woodbridge had made it clear he "hates to be
called a doubles specialist".
</P>
<P>
The Australian felt good about the week and was eager to build
on what he calls a "lucky break" getting into the main draw which
allows him to defend the ranking points he gained last year at the
Heineken Open, Shanghai when he was a quarterfinalist.
</P>
<P>
"I have nothing to lose and this is like an upward graph for me
right now," said Woodbridge. "I'm just hoping for match wins this
year because of my poor singles. I'm working on my game and it's
promising. I've got my goals and I want to get back to where I've
been."
</P>
<P>
Woodbridge had to fight so hard to escape from the match. In
the second set Lee led 2-0 and had three points for 3-0, but when
Woodbridge managed to break back and win 25 of 29 points, he felt
things were on the move even though it continued to be very tight
till the end.
</P>
<P>
"He is a very good player and I realised that when I played him
in qualifiers. That was a high standard match and he showed no
weaknesses and I can see no reason why he can't be in the top 100,
" said Woodbridge. "I tried to step up the pace, hit my forehand
and get in (to the net)."
</P>
<P>
In other matches, Jonas Bjorkman of Sweden managed to work
through a second set hiccup and defeated Lars Burgsmuller of
Germany. The fifth seeded Swede reached the quarterfinals with a
score of 7-5, 3-6, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
The qualifier from Sweden, Andreas Vinciguerra, made short work
of American Cecil Mamiit 6-1, 6-3. There is a Swede guaranteed of
a place in the semifinals because Bjorkman will play Vinciguerra.
</P>
<P>
In the doubles, world No. 1 Leander Paes and Maheshi Bhupathi
made a solid step forward in their defence, thrashing Chinese pair
of Li si and Yang Jingzhu 6-2, 6-1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
