<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines to Be Ready for Concord by Yearend </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said Wednesday that a preparatory commission tasked to
study proposed economic reforms through the Constitutional
Corrections for Development (Concord) process would complete its
work by the yearend.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a radio interview, Estrada said the Preparatory
Commission on Constitutional Reforms (PCCR) chaired by retired
Chief Justice Andres Narvasa has buckled down to work on the
economic reform proposals.
</P>
<P>
"They are very busy now. And hopefully, they will meet the
deadline on December 31," the president said.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the public anew to support his Concord
initiative which he said is a vital element of his program to help
the masses rise above poverty and reinforce the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
He said his administration is doing all it can within its power
to liberate the majority of Filipinos from poverty, including
pushing the Concord process, even though it continues to encounter
opposition from some sectors.
</P>
<P>
Part of these long-term solutions is the implementation of
economic reforms through the Concord that will remove restrictions
on the entry of foreign capital into the country, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that allowing 100-percent foreign ownership of public
utilities and local businesses will encourage overseas investors
to pour their resources and technologies into the country, which
in turn will invigorate local industries and create more jobs for
Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
The present constitution bars foreigners from owning land and
gaining a controlling stake in local businesses, including public
utilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
