<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Inter-clan Fighting Kills Nine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, October 6 (Xinhua) -- At least nine people were
killed and more than a dozen others wounded in inter-clan
fightings for farmland ownership in the remote villages of Bulo
Ahmed and Kulmis, about 110 kilometers north of the capital on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
 According to reports reaching here on Wednesday, the two
villages exchanged heavy gunfire with assault refiles, rocket
propelled grenades and machine guns.
</P>
<P>
The fighting has forced dozens of families to flee their small
huts.
</P>
<P>
Clan elders from the various subclans of Shidleh in Jowhar town
have rushed to the fighting scene to broker for peace. Latest
reports from the villages said that the area has returned to calm,
but the tension is still high with the dispute unsolved.
</P>
<P>
Other reports said the fightings within Badih-Addeh clan for
land ownership have claimed more than ten lives and wounded many
others in villages near Bulo Burto district of Hiran region.
</P>
<P>
These emerging fightings have aroused concerns that Somali
unarmed societies, clans and subclans will get deeply involved
into inter-clan killings in the war-ravaged African Horn country.
</P>
<P>
Some of these clans are even challenging the main armed
communities who seem to have tired of fighting or weakened as a
result of earlier confrontations.
</P>
<P>
Earlier non-armed communities of the Bantu, Biyomal, Rer Hamar
and Garreh clans have formed alliances against the faction led by
Hussein Mohamed Aidid and vowed to eliminate his forces from the
fertile regions of southern Somalia.
</P>
<P>
According to Aden Hassan, a weapons dealer in Mogadishu, the
minority communities are buying a large amount of ammunition and
weapons, ready to launch attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
