<HEADLINE> Sino-Foreign University Programs Grant Overseas Degrees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nanchang, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Some universities on the
Mainland and those in other countries and in Hong Kong have
reached agreements on granting degrees from those universities
overseas and in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
A member of the State Council's Academic Degree Committee made
the announcement here today at a seminar on Sino-Foreign
University Projects. The programs include an MBA from Beijing
University and Stanford University and an MBA with concentration
on hi-tech administration from Qinghua University and Arizona
State University.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the program is to train better administrators
which are badly needed in China.
</P>
<P>
The Committee says that there are 30 such programs in all
involving 27 universities from the Mainland and 25 from the U.S.,
Britain, Australia, France, the Netherlands, Norway, and Thailand,
and 2 from Hong Kong. They include State University of New York at
Buffalo, New South Wales University, and Greenwich University.
</P>
<P>
Li Jun, the deputy-director of the Committee, says that the
joint university programs benefit the higher education system here
and help China get high quality teaching staff, materials, and
methods from overseas.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese institutions need to be well qualified to be
involved in the graduate program and degrees don't meet their
standards will not be recognized, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
