<HEADLINE> JTC to Expand Business in China: JTC Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A senior Singapore business
leader said Wednesday that the Jurong Town Corporation (JTC) will
expand business in China.
</P>
<P>
"Building on what we have achieved in Suzhou, we hope to do
more business in China," Major General Lim Neo Chian, chairman of
JTC, which contributes more than one quarter of the country's
manufacturing output, said at a press conference here to release
JTC annual report 1998/1999 and announce the corporation's future
plans.
</P>
<P>
"My direction is to do more rather than to do less in China,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Lim noted that JTC's international operation has done well
despite the Asian economic crisis and projects by its overseas arm
JTC International (JTCI) in both industrial park development and
consultancy have made good progress.
</P>
<P>
He expected that JTCI will earn quite an amount of net profit
from its China branch XinSu company in Suzhou this year.
</P>
<P>
On fixed asset investment by investors in JTCI's industrial
parks in foreign countries, the JTC chairman said ready-built
factories in the China-Singapore Suzhou Industrial Park have 57
customers to date, investing more than 400 million U.S. dollars
and generating more than 5,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
Occupancy is 91 percent for standard factories and 60 percent
for flatted ones there, he added.
</P>
<P>
Data released by JTC shows that the figure is the highest among
JTCI's 19 industrial park and infrastructure projects in China,
the Philippines, Thailand, India, Vietnam, Indonesia and other
places.
</P>
<P>
Referring to JTCI's consultancy business in China, Lim said its
consultancy subsidiary, JTCI Consultants (Suzhou) Co. Ltd. (JTCI
Suzhou) has successfully expanded from its base in Suzhou to other
parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Established in 1994, JTCI Suzhou has since undertaken projects
in Shanghai, Baoding and Chongqing and is vigorously pursuing
Zhejiang, Tianjin and Beijing, Lim said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
