<HEADLINE> Pak Denies Indian Charge of Cross-Border Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Wednesday dismissed
as baseless India's allegations of cross-border terrorism, saying
such "baseless charges" have never been backed up with facts or
evidence.
</P>
<P>
The denial was made by a Foreign Office spokesman here in
response to Indian Foreign Secretary K. Raghunath's reported
statement Tuesday that resumption of dialogue with Pakistan was
possible if the latter ended cross-border terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"These allegations are made as a smoke-screen behind which India
continues with its state-sponsored terrorism" in Indian-held
Kashmir, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the fact that Raghunath had linked resumption
of talks with stopping of alleged cross-border terrorism by
Pakistan, the spokesman said this kind of precondition for
resumption of dialogue is unacceptable to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has consistently rejected the "baseless Indian
allegations of support for the so-called cross-border terrorism,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked about India's test-firing of the surface-to air
missile, Akash, on Tuesday, he said it was another step to
destabilize peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
The test of the Akash missile "is yet another destabilizing
step by India for peace and security in the region," he charged.
</P>
</TEXT>
