<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Further Open Aviation Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria is encouraging foreign and
 indigenous airlines to compete with the Nigeria Airways on
international routes to re-invigorate the country's declining
aviation sector.
</P>
<P>
The message was contained in a new aviation policy unfolded by
Aviation Minister Olusegun Agagu at the opening of the first
International Civil Aviation Forum held in Abuja Tuesday, reported
the Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the new policy is aimed to develop Lagos
into the hub of African air transportation and travelling system.
</P>
<P>
Under this policy, private airlines would be allowed to compete
on international routes with the Nigeria Airways, the monopoly of
Bilateral Air Services Agreement (BASA).
</P>
<P>
Besides the liberalization of designated carriers on
international routes, other measures are also underway to boost
indigenous airline participation in international operations,
Agagu said.
</P>
<P>
He said these include simplifying aircraft flight clearance by
removal of military clearance and allowing foreign airlines into
more than one entry point in the country provided they pay
commercial compensation.
</P>
<P>
President Olusegun Obasanjo had early in July directed the
Ministry of Aviation to produce, among others, an Action Program
to resuscitate the aviation industry of the country.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, subsequently, produced an action plan in such
areas as airspace and airport management, safety and economic
regulation, revival of the national carrier, stimulation of
foreign airline participation, reinforcement of manpower
development and development of Lagos into a hub.
</P>
<P>
According to Agagu, privatization of the airline is the
ultimate goal of the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
