<HEADLINE> 2 Lebanese Wounded in Israeli Shelling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Two Lebanese civilians were
wounded Wednesday morning during Israeli shelling on south
Lebanon, Lebanese security sources said.
</P>
<P>
A man and his child were injured when Israeli artillery troops
fired shells on the village of Furoun on the edge of the Israeli
occupied border zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Finnish battalion's position inside the village was also hit
by the shells, which only caused some damages to houses, the
sources added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, Israeli warplanes also blasted other
mountainous areas and villages in and outside the border enclave,
which are believed to be hideouts for guerillas of Hezbollah, or
Party of God.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 to protect its north from Lebanese guerrillas'
cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Since then, Lebanon's resistance movement spearheaded by the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah has been fighting to oust Israeli troops
out of the country.
</P>
<P>
The 4500-strong United Nations Interim Forces in Lebanon made
up of troops from nine countries are installed to help the
Lebanese government to restore authority over its land in the
south. 
</P>
</TEXT>
