<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- France's exports to the United Arab Emirates (UAE)
reached more than 1 billion U.S. dollars in the first seven months
of this year, up 53 percent compared to the same period last year,
the Khaleej Times daily reported on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, France's imports from the UAE during the same period
reached 30 million dollars, down by 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
France saw a sharp increase in its exports to UAE of
agricultural and food products, automobiles, electrical and
electronic equipments and consumer goods during the period, said
the report.
</P>
<P>
DUBAI -- The number of companies operating in the Jebel Ali
free zone in Dubai has increased to 1,600 from 88 countries,
making it the largest such zone throughout an area from Europe to
East Asia, said an official at the Dubai harbor.
</P>
<P>
Total investments in the zone are expected to exceed the two-
billion-U.S.-dollar level this year, the Arabic-language daily Al
Hayat reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Morocco has called on American, Canadian and British
oil companies to engage in prospecting for petroleum and natural
gas in the country, the Arabic-language daily Al Hayat reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The appeal was made on the sideline of a recently-held
International Energy Conference in Huston, U.S.A..
</P>
<P>
Morocco discovered large oil fields in the rocky central
regions of the Atlantic Ocean in the early 1980's. And unlimited
amount of petroleum exists in the southern region of Torfaya, but
the high cost of extracting and refining it makes the project
economically unfeasible.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The Jordanian government has decided to bear the debts
of Jordan's petroleum refineries amounting to 211 million dinars
(300 million U.S. dollars) instead of those of the Royal Jordanian
Airlines to facilitate its privatization process.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring of the national carrier involves the
separation of its auxiliary units, namely, the duty free market,
catering, supply, maintenance of engines and the training center,
as well as the setting up of independent companies to undertake
those units. It will then be sold to the private sector to settle
internal debts, the Egyptian daily Alam Al Yom quoted the official
as saying Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
