<HEADLINE> Writethru: BJP-led Alliance Ahead in Indian Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The BJP-led National
Democratic Alliance (NDA) was surging ahead, winning 24 of the 34
Lok Sabha seats and leading 179 of 323 constituencies from which
trends were available at 17:00 local time Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Congress and its allies were ahead in 106 constituencies,
bagging eight seats, while other parties were ahead in 38
constituencies, bagging two seats.
</P>
<P>
In Delhi, the BJP, which has bagged four of the seven Lok Sabha
seats and established a convincing lead in the remaining three
constituencies, is all set to sweep the parliamentary polls.
</P>
<P>
In 1998 elections, the BJP only won one seat in the national
capital.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee is leading in Lucknow
constituency by 109,654 votes against his Congress rival Karan
Singh.
</P>
<P>
Congress President Sonia Gandhi was leading by 2,000 votes
against her BJP rival Sushma Swaraj in Bellary Lok Sabha
constituency.
</P>
<P>
Home Minister L.K. Advani retained his seat in Gandhinagar,
defeating Congress candidate, former chief election commissioner
T. N. Seshan.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after winning his seat by a massive margin of
188,000 votes, Advani said that the trends were in conformity with
expectations and projections by various opinion and exit polls.
</P>
<P>
He said that the BJP-led NDA will get a clear majority to form
the new government as voters appear to have favored
re-installation of Vajpayee as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the landslide victory in Delhi, he said it was
the first time since 1977 that the BJP was winning all the seats
in the national capital.
</P>
<P>
He termed the trends as "positive vote" for the BJP and its
allies. 
</P>
