<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turning HK into World-Class City: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), made his
pledge here Wednesday to turn Hong Kong into a world-class,
knowledge-based cosmopolitan city.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong should not only be a major Chinese city, but could
become the most cosmopolitan city in Asia, enjoying a status
comparable to that of New York in North America and London in
Europe," said Tung in his third annual policy address to the
Legislative Council Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong is faced with three momentous changes,
namely, globalization of the world's economy, rapid economic
development on the mainland, and economic restructuring, in the
move towards a new era.
</P>
<P>
"The current situation calls for urgency in action," Tung said.
"We must face the new reality: Hong Kong must position itself
firmly and clearly in the global economy."
</P>
<P>
Tung, who initiated the plan to develop Hong Kong into a world-
class city in his last policy address, said Hong Kong already
possesses many of the key features common to New York and London.
</P>
<P>
"For example, we are already an international center of finance
and a popular tourist destination, and hold leading positions in
trade and transportation," he said.
</P>
<P>
"These are all pillars of our economy. If we can consolidate
our existing economic pillars and continue to build on our
strengths, we should be able to become world-class," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Then, like New York and London, we will play a pivotal role in
the global economy, be home to a host of multi-national companies
and provide services to the entire region," he said.
</P>
<P>
"On the other hand, we must admit that Hong Kong lags behind
other international world-class cities in many respects, in
particular human capital and living environment," he continued.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the unique advantages of Hong Kong, Tung said, "We
have the thriving mainland next to us. We are a melting pot for
Chinese and Western cultures. We are a high liberal and open
society. Our institutions are well established."
</P>
<P>
"Our per capita income is on a par with other affluent
economies. Our infrastructure is comprehensive. The rule of law is
secure and we have well-established regulatory and management
systems," he added.
</P>
<P>
"With such a strong foundation, we should be able to build on
our strengths and develop modern and knowledge-intensive
industries, erect new pillars in our economy and open up new and
better prospects," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
