<HEADLINE> Nigeria Justifies Troop Withdrawal from S.Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's Foreign Minister Alhaji
Lamido justified the country's withdrawal of troops from Sierra
Leone, saying that the crisis had caused the nation heavily in
lives and resources.
</P>
<P>
The minister told reporters on Tuesday, "We have been there for
a number of years trying to restore democracy and it has been
quite a lot of burden to us in terms of the cost in human lives
and also in resources," reported the Vanguard, a major Nigerian
newspaper Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the Nigerian troops in the West African
Peacekeeping Force or ECOMOG will continue to stay there at the
moment for the current troubles in Sierra Leone's peace process.
</P>
<P>
He revealed that he had met Sierra Leone's rebel leader Foday
Sankoh three weeks ago, and Sankoh "seemed more than willing to
surrender to ECOMOG", led by Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
When talking about the future United Nations peacekeeping force
in Sierra Leone, he said it will be a neutral arrangement,
despite the United Nations is trying to adopt the ECOMOG forces.
He said  the commander of the U.N. force would not be a Nigerian
like that is the situation in the ECOMOG. 
</P>
