<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Further Develop Basic Education: Chief Executive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- In his policy address here
Wednesday, Chief Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) Tung Chee Hwa once again stressed the importance of
improving basic education in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
One of the important policies is to delegate full authority and
responsibility to schools and their front-line staff as far as
possible.
</P>
<P>
This is resulting in a leaner departmental management structure,
he said, adding that at the same time, measures are also being
implemented to strengthen school-based management and enhance the
schools' accountability.
</P>
<P>
Whole-day primary schooling is also an important part of Hong
Kong's efforts to raise the quality of education, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the percentage of primary students enjoying
whole-day schooling has risen from 19 percent in 1997 to 32
percent this year. By September 2002, the percentage will have
doubled to reach the earlier interim target of 60 percent, he said.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government has set the long-term target of achieving
whole-day schooling for almost all primary school students by the
2007-2008 school year, he added.
</P>
<P>
To help improve quality education, the government has set up a
5-billion-HK dollar (641 million U.S. dollars) Quality Education
Fund to support school-based innovative practices and to improve
the quality of teaching and learning, he said.
</P>
<P>
To date, the government has granted some 580 million HK dollars
(74.3 million U.S. dollars) to over 1,000 projects, benefiting
more than 600,000 kindergarten, primary and secondary students, he
said, adding that the projects have improved the effectiveness of
both teaching and learning, and have encouraged the teachers and
principals involved to try out more creative ways of teaching.
</P>
<P>
Promoting information technology in education is also an
important government policy concerning education.
</P>
<P>
Since the publication of the five-year strategy on information
technology in education last November, the government has offered
schools cash grants for purchasing computers, provided 120 schools
each with an information technology coordinator, and begun
information technology training for teachers.
</P>
<P>
Within the next five years, Hong Kong school children will be
able to master the general application of information technology,
connect to the Internet, and be equipped to become life-long
learners with inquiring and creative minds, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government will also provide comprehensive training
programs for school principals. The first program is scheduled to
commence in the 2000-2001 school year. All newly-appointed
principals will have to complete the first part of the program
prior to appointment, he said.
</P>
<P>
Language ability is also stressed. By 2005, all serving
language teachers must have attained the benchmarks established
for those teaching English in junior secondary schools and
Putonghua in primary schools.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government will also provide support for the
development of quality private schools and Direct Subsidy Scheme
schools, as a move to introduce greater diversity and to give
parents more choice, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
