<HEADLINE> Federal Troops May Cross Terek River in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev
said Wednesday that Russian federal troops may cross the Terek
River in Chechnya in its latest campaign to root out Islamic
rebels in the breakaway republic.
</P>
<P>
"Everything will depend on the situation," he said, noting
that some of the Russian units have already advanced to as far as
Terek.
</P>
<P>
All federal troops have reached the Terokumsky irrigation
channel laid along Terek at a distance of 10 kilometers, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Terek River passes about 15 kilometers north of Grozny,
the regional capital.
</P>
<P>
Sergeyev said that the federal grouping continues "to create a
security zone around the republic" in the first stage of the
operation.
</P>
<P>
He said federal forces, which had encountered "pocket
resistance" from the rebels, might face large-scale military
operations by Chechen formations.
</P>
<P>
"We are prepared for everything," he said.
</P>
<P>
Russia lost two warplanes, one Su-24 attack plane and a Su-24
bomber, earlier this week and the fate of the pilots remained
unknown.
</P>
<P>
Search and rescue operation continues to locate the pilots. "
We have not lost hope for saving them," the defense minister said.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, former Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin voiced his opposition to the federal units' crossing of
the Terek River, warning of inevitable large-scale battles and
heavy losses.
</P>
<P>
Stepashin said he told President Boris Yeltsin the same thing
during the 1994-1996 Chechen war. Federal troops crossed the
river then and the war ended disastrously. Some 90,000 people
perished in that war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
