<HEADLINE> UNICEF Rejects Responsibility for Arsenic Contamination in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF)
on Wednesday denied that it was responsible for the arsenic
contamination in Bangladesh reportedly resulting from excessive
extraction of ground water by UNICEF-provided tube wells.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference here, visiting Deputy Executive
Director of UNICEF Karin Holmgrunn Sham Poo said the organization
was not the introducer of tube wells in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We have come to Bangladesh to ensure pathogen-free safe
drinking water and mobilized people to use tube-well water in this
regard," she said, adding that extraction of ground water was not
the only cause of arsenic contamination.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF has taken a multi-sectoral approach to address some
problems in Bangladesh, such as mobilization of people against
women repression, maternal mortality, acid burns and arsenic
contamination, she said.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with Local Government, Rural Development and
Cooperative Minister Zillur Rahman on Wednesday, the UNICEF deputy
executive director assured the Bangladeshi government of the
organization's continued assistance to control arsenic
contamination in the ground water of the country.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF would strengthen its assistance to prevent
arsenic-related health hazards and to combat the arsenic menace in
Bangladesh, she said.
</P>
<P>
Rahman told the UNICEF official that the causes of arsenic
contamination in Bangladesh have been identified and the
government has taken immediate steps to ensure the supply of pure
drinking water and other rehabilitation measures in the affected
areas.
</P>
<P>
Out of 64 districts in the country, 59 are affected and arsenic
contamination level is high in the ground water in 211 out of the
country's 460 thanas (sub-districts), he said.
</P>
<P>
"To control this national disaster, the government is working
with the donors, development partners and non-governmental
organizations for launching a collective endeavor to contain the
menace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arsenic contamination in tube-well water was first detected in
the country's northern region in 1993 and arsenic-related diseases
have taken on an epidemic form in 21 districts of the country,
killing hundreds of people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
