<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Launch Virtual Global Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia is expected to
launch a virtual global exchange that offers listing and trading
of financial and non-financial products in multicurrency in its
offshore financial center of Labuan in March 2000, Bank Negara
(State Bank) Governor Ali Abul Hassan Sulaiman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Products to be listed on the exchange, known as Labuan
International Financial Exchange (LIFE), will include mutual
funds, bonds, derivatives, insurance-linked products and possibly
intellectual properties, the central bank chief said.
</P>
<P>
LIFE would be market-driven, run by participants of the market
and adopting best international practices of offshore exchanges
in the world, he said in his keynote address at the fourth Labuan
Annual Lecture services in Labuan, off Sabah, East Malaysia. His
speech was read out by the bank's assistant governor Awang Adek
Hussin.
</P>
<P>
"Its rules will be flexible to allow dual listings as well as
investors and companies from other jurisdictions to tap capital,"
Bernama news agency quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
The cost of listing would be competitive and trading could be
conducted 24 hours a day, the central bank governor said, adding
that more importantly, there will be plenty of spin-offs to the
other offshore players to participate in the form of providing
custodial, depository, clearing and trustee services.
</P>
<P>
He said that LIFE would be developed and wholly-owned by the
Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) to draw on its resources and
experience.
</P>
<P>
LIFE will be regulated under the Labuan Offshore Securities
Industry Act (LOSIA) 1998 that also regulates the fund management
business in Labuan.
</P>
<P>
Through LOSIA, The Labuan Offshore Financial Services Authority
(LOFSA), a one-stop agency that focuses on the development and
promotion of Labuan as an International Offshore Financial Center,
would be the regulator for LIFE, not the SC as on the on-shore
capital market.
</P>
<P>
According to Ali Abul, the LOFSA would be investing in a
gateway in the World Wide Web so that offshore players could link
to the gateway and interface with their customers.
</P>
<P>
It will provide comprehensive information on the Labuan
International Offshore Financial Center (IOFC) and customers will
have interactive access, via the gateway to financial products and
services offered by the various players in the center, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ali Abul said the idea behind the gateway is to ensure no
duplication of investment by the offshore players and LOFSA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1000 Nigerians Feared drowned by Flood in Niger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- No fewer than 1,000 residents in
Kwara State, west of Nigeria, were feared drowned and about
300,000 displaced by flooding in Niger River in the country.
</P>
<P>
About 400 villages are believed to have been submerged by the
rampaging flood, the Vanguard, a leading Nigerian newspaper,
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Worst hit were towns and villages like Pategi, Lafiaji,
Tsaragi, Tsonga and Bacita in Kwara State where the sugar
plantation of the Nigerian Sugar Company was submerged.
</P>
<P>
The state's Governor Mohammed Lawal immediately went to the
flooding areas to assess the damage, while some of the survivors
blamed Nigeria Electric Power Agency (NEPA), which is in charge of
some dams on the upper stream of the river, for the situation.
</P>
<P>
They said the release of excess water from the dams that caused
the flood.
</P>
<P>
But a NEPA official denied that the opening of the dams'
spillway gates caused the flood, explaining that this would be
done soon.
</P>
<P>
The official said: "We have not opened any of the gates but we
are now calling on the state government to enlighten their people
to clear off the flood basin where people are staying illegally
because those reservoirs are now full to capacity and the spillway
gates will be opened at any moment from now."
</P>
<P>
The massive inflow of water comes from Rivers Kaduna and Niger
as well as heavy rainfall experienced in the areas this year.
</P>
<P>
Senator Ahmed Zuruq from Kwara threatened to sue NEPA for
damages arising from the disaster.
</P>
<P>
According to Zuruq, NEPA has reneged on its promise to release
excess water from the dams every four years and to the detriment
of the people of the area.
</P>
<P>
Alhaji Lade, chairman of a Local Government in the flooded
area, said over 500 people from his local government area alone
were drowned in the flood.
</P>
<P>
Describing the disaster as the worst in recent times, he
appealed to the government to relocate the people of the area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
