<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Formulate Masterplan for Banking Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will formulate a
masterplan to address several issues related to the domestic
banking industry in a holistic manner, Bank Negara (State Bank)
Malaysia (BNM) Governor Ali Abul Hassan Sulaiman said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The comprehensive and coherent masterplan aims at developing
the banking sector and identifying winning strategies to be
pursued over the short to long term, he said in Labuan, off Sabah,
East Malaysia, Bernama news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
In formulating the masterplan, BNM would be assisted by
reputable international consultants, Ali Abul, who is also
chairman of Labuan Offshore Financial Services Authority (LOFSA),
said in an address at the fourth Labuan Annual Lecture series
there, which was read out by the bank's assistant governor Awang
Adek Hussin.
</P>
<P>
"The masterplan will be formulated in consultation with the
industry and all other stakeholders. We expect the plan to be
completed during the first half of 2000," he was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the issues related to the banking industry included how
liberalization should be carried out in relation to the financial
markets and infrastructures, regulatory rules and policies, and
management capabilities.
</P>
<P>
He said, "It is the vision and aspirations of BNM to create a
strong, progressive and competitive financial system. One which is
able to withstand future shocks without adversely affecting
macroeconomic stability. One that is able to support the nation's
economy effectively and facilitate the economic transformation
process in order for the country to attain developed status by
2020." 
</P>
</TEXT>
