<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Train Crash Death Toll Rises to 27 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The number of people confirmed
dead in the London train crash has risen to 27, but police warned
on Wednesday that the death toll is likely to rise further.
</P>
<P>
The crash happened on Tuesday morning when the three-carriage
service run by Thames Trains from Paddington to Bedwyn in
Wiltshire collided with the London-bound Great Western 125 express
train from Cheltenham at Ladbroke Grove.
</P>
<P>
The initial Health and Safety Executive investigation suggests
the Thames train passed one red and two yellow warning signals,
ploughing into the Great Western which had been given a green
light.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Assistant Commissioner Andy Trotter, of the Metropolitan
Police, said the search for bodies would concentrate on the front
first-class carriage of the Great Western train, which was "
devastated" by fire.
</P>
<P>
The grisly search was suspended on Tuesday night with the
emergency services sure there was no one else left alive on either
train.
</P>
<P>
Of the 27 confirmed dead, 12 bodies remain at the scene but he
said he hoped they would all be removed by the end of Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Police say the search will be a long and laborious task
</P>
<P>
Trotter refused to comment on speculation about the final death
toll but said there were about 500 people on the Great Western
train and at least 100 on the Thames train.
</P>
<P>
As well as the 27 confirmed dead, 165 were taken to hospital.
</P>
<P>
An urgent public inquiry has been ordered by Deputy Prime
Minister John Prescott.
</P>
<P>
He also ordered Health and Safety Executive investigators to
issue a preliminary statement on the crash within days, to avoid a
delay like that which followed the Southall rail crash.
</P>
<P>
British officials pledged money on Wednesday to make Britain's
railways safer as rescuers cut through the charred and twisted
wreckage of a London train crash fearing they could find up to 90
bodies.
</P>
<P>
Amid charges that the Tuesday morning tragedy was the result of
a ramshackle, underfunded rail system, Junior Transport Minister
Lord Gus Macdonald said everything would be done to improve safety.
</P>
<P>
The death toll so far makes it Britain's worst rail disaster in
a decade.
</P>
<P>
Paddington, the capital's rail gateway to western Britain and
terminus for a high-speed link to Heathrow airport, was closed
after the crash and was not due to reopen before Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
