<HEADLINE> Nigeria Resumes Open Tenders for Gov. Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
reintroduced open tenders for public works for the first time over
the past 10 years to step up transparency and accountability in
government business.
</P>
<P>
At a ceremony to open bids for 74 road projects held in capital
Abuja on Tuesday, Minister of Works and Housing Tony Anenih said
that in the past Tenders Boards had become moribund as the award
of contracts were carried out without due reference to the
relevant laid down procedures and government financial
regulations.
</P>
<P>
He noted the bidding session was a demonstration of
government's commitment to instituting transparency and
accountability in government business, New Nigerian daily reported
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed the hope that the reintroduction of open
tenders policy would encourage competitiveness in the choice of
contractors for public sector projects.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of about 492 companies tendered for 74 road
projects all over the west African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
