<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Damaged Equipment Blamed for Nuclear Leakage in South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Damaged equipment is believed to
have produced the heavy water leak at the Wolsong Nuclear Plant of
North Kyongdang Province, 305 kilometers southeast of Seoul.
</P>
<P>
South Korea Electric Power Corporation Deputy Chairman Park
Yong-taek told a press conference Wednesday that the heavy water
leaked out from the damaged pipe of a seal connecting the motor
and the pump of the No. 3 reactor.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know why it was damaged. We will have to wait about
a week until after a thorough check is completed, Park said.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 environmental and civic groups across South Korea,
including the Korean Federation for the Environmental Movement,
have demonstrated at government complexes, demanding a joint
government-civilian team to probe the accident.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-two workers were exposed to low-level radiation when
the accident occurred at around 7 p.m. local time Monday during a
preventive safety inspection of the cooling water pump of the No.
3 reactor, which had been out of service since September 23 for
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Science and Technology Ministry said all the
leaked 45 liters of heavy water has been retrieved inside the
plant and the leak didn't pollute the environment and it didn't
pose health hazards.
</P>
<P>
The exposure of the 22 workers of the South Korean Power
Corporation was far below the limited level of yearly average 50
mSV since the nuclear reactor was not in operation, the ministry
said.
</P>
<P>
The 22 workers were exposed to radiation measured at between 0.
006 mSv and 4.5 mSv. Nineteen workers were put back to work while
another three are under special care for overexposure.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said a team of nuclear specialists is
investigating details of the accident.
</P>
<P>
The leak was the smallest one of the past four accidents but it
was the first time that people was reportedly exposed to radiation
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The 700,000-kilowatt No. 3 reactor went into commercial
operation last year as South Korea's first pressurized heavy water
reactor, which is modeled after Canada's CANDU reactors.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear leak came five days after a disastrous nuclear
accident in Japan in which at least 49 people were exposed to
radiation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
