<HEADLINE> Top IDF Educator Warns Against Tolerance of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- One of the lessons Israel can
learn from NATO's onslaught on Yugoslavia is that the world may be
becoming more tolerant of civilian casualties, said a senior
Israeli military officer.
</P>
<P>
"During the war, NATO forces repeatedly hit civilian Serbian
targets and caused heavy civilian casualties. These attacks were
explained as the prices that could not be avoided in war," said
Brig. Gen. Yaacov Amidror, commander of military colleges of the
Israel Defense Forces (IDF).
</P>
<P>
"Yet the IDF's Grapes of Wrath Operation in 1996 was halted by
the American government in light of the mistaken Israeli strike on
Lebanese civilians," he said in an article published in the latest
edition of Ma'arachot, the Israeli defense establishment's
academic bimonthly.
</P>
<P>
And "now we have to see whether the NATO behavior in the Kosovo
war has the lowered standard of harming civilians" he added.
</P>
<P>
Israel has to be aware that there is a "new approach in the
relationship of the world and nations considered to be harming
international morality," he warned.
</P>
<P>
NATO launched air strikes against Yugoslavia from March to
early June, causing heavy civilian casualties and damages
estimated at about 200 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
