<HEADLINE> ASEAN Shippers Ask for Code of Conduct in Shipping Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Federation of ASEAN
Shippers' Council (FASC) Wednesday appealed to governments in the
region to implement an acceptable code of conduct governing the
affairs of the liner shipping industry.
</P>
<P>
The members of the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development (UNCTAD) should also develop such a code of conduct at
the 10th UNCTAD meeting scheduled in Bangkok in February 2000,
FASC Chairman Vicharn Nivatvongs said at a press conference after
the opening of FASC's 22nd annual general meeting here.
</P>
<P>
This should also be a pertinent agenda for General Agreement on
Trade and Services (GATS) 2000 and the World Trade Organization
(WTO), he said.
</P>
<P>
FASC members reiterated at the meeting Wednesday the need for a
formal prior consultation mechanism to be established for more
open dialogues and consultations between shipping lines and
shippers.
</P>
<P>
The mechanism should also provide for government intervention
or arbitration if no agreements are reached by both sides, the
FASC chief said.
</P>
<P>
The very high and rapidly increasing levels of terminal
handling charges with little transparency, documentation fees and
other charges were the major concerns among FASC members, he said,
suggesting these charges be part of an all-in freight rate and not
be charged separately.
</P>
<P>
The three-day FASC 22nd annual general meeting, hosted by the
National Shippers' Council, brought together shipper organizations
from both within and outside the region to discuss and exchange
views on various subjects involving maritime transport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
