<P>
CAIRO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A pro-government Egyptian
newspaper criticized Israel on Wednesday for lack of actions and
steps to support its proclaimed readiness to resume peace
negotiations with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Over the past three months, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
"has displayed a gift for procrastinating and playing on words,"
the Egyptian Gazette newspaper said in a commentary.
</P>
<P>
Syria demands to resume the negotiations with Israel at the
point where they broke off. But the Israelis "are balking at"
Syria's demand and "playing tricks" to depict Syria as the one
unwilling to make peace, said the paper, which usually mirrors the
thinking of Egypt's leadership.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli peace talks came to a halt after a series of
suicide bombings in Israel in early 1996. After Barak was elected
in May and took office in July, both countries expressed readiness
to restart their talks for a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
The two countries are disputing over Israeli troop withdrawal
from the Golan Heights that the Jewish state captured from Syria
in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Syria insists that the talks be resumed on the basis of a
promise by late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin that Israel
would pull back from all of the Golan Heights in return for peace
with Syria. But Barak has, so far, failed to respond positively.
</P>
<P>
The Israelis are taking aim at Syria to force it into a tight
corner, a campaign aimed at pressuring Damascus into sitting at
the negotiating table without a pre-set agenda, the
English-language newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
It accused Barak of only saying "fine and conciliatory words"
and failing to translate his words into actions.
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural speech at the Israeli Knesset (parliament),
Barak called on Syrian President Hafez al-Assad to "walk (with
him) through the door of opportunities and take the necessary
decisions - even if they are painful - for the sake of the
children of both countries, for a peace of courage and dignity."
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian paper urged Barak to keep his promise to make
"peace of the brave."
</P>
<P>
It is Israel that needs to 'take the necessary decisions even
if they are painful' to realize peace with the Syrians by pulling
out of the Golan Heights, it stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
