<HEADLINE> No Fresh Probe in Kisangani Clash: Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Political Commissar of Uganda's ruling National Resistance
Movement James Wapakhabulo will lead a delegation to Kigali on
October 11 to intensify efforts of mending ties with Rwanda,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Both sides sustained heavy losses during the August 13-17
clashes, the first sign of crack in the bilateral relations since
the two allies sent troops to back the DRC rebels soon after the
rebellion broke out in August of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The joint investigation team came up with a report in
September blaming the Ugandan side for the clashes.
</P>
<P>
The Uganda Military High Command reportedly rejected the
report, saying it was too biased and inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
Since then the two neighboring states have been making efforts
to normalize relations although no breakthrough is in sight.
</P>
