<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Rise For Fifth Straight Trading Day in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices rose for the fifth
consecutive trading day in Tokyo Wednesday, led by buying on
shares which benefit from the issuance of new 2,000 yen banknotes.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange surged 112.27 points, or 0.63
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 17,896.42.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, added 2.47 points or 0.16 percent to 1,512.
53.
</P>
<P>
Traders said market focus was on issues expected to benefit
from the planned issuance of a 2,000 yen banknote. Japanese Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi said Tuesday the Bank of Japan will roll out
the banknotes to mark the new millennium and Japan's hosting of
the Group of Eight summit in Okinawa in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Expectations for additional economic stimulus measures under
Obuchi's new three-party coalition government was another factor
to promote stock prices, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went up to 490.87 million shares
from 461.75 million shares Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Itochu, a major Japanese trading firm, was the day's volume
leader.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 731 to 443 despite the rises in both the Nikkei and TOPIX,
with 149 issues closing unchanged.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
