<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Chief Executive Vows to Introduce Reforms, Maintain Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive
of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), said here
Wednesday
that the SAR government will reform some of the existing systems
and
procedures to adapt to changes and demands of the new era.
</P>
<P>
Delivering his annual policy address, Tung said the government
has been determined to remove any weaknesses through reform during
the past two years.
</P>
<P>
"Since Hong Kong has enjoyed a high degree of autonomy
following
its return, it is natural that the community has greater
expectations of the government," said Tung. "Moreover, there is
still room for improvement."
</P>
<P>
He classified the reforms into three types. The first is
related
to the improvement to some market mechanisms and injecting greater
vitality into the markets. The second is the rationalization of
the
government's basic policies or delivery systems. The third is the
modernization of the civil service structure which involves
government efficiency.
</P>
<P>
He said the reforms of the first type, which include the
strengthening of the linked exchange rate regime and the merger of
the
two exchanges, will remove some of the weaknesses that surfaced in
the
financial turmoil and further strengthen Hong Kong's position as a
financial center.
</P>
<P>
Under the reform of rationalizing the government's basic
policies
or administrative structure, the government will launch education
reforms and the dissolution of the Municipal Councils, he
explained.
</P>
<P>
As for the modernization of the civil service, productivity
enhancement, and entry pay adjustment, these reforms are being
implemented gradually after consultation and careful deliberation
with
the aim to improve services and efficiency, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Tung pointed out that the Basic Law underpins Hong Kong's
institutions and enables the Hong Kong SAR to build a quality
society with unique
characteristics, adding that the institutions provide the basis
for
Hong Kong's development.
</P>
<P>
"The rule of law, a clean administration, freedom of the press,
protection of the freedoms and rights of the individual, are all
essential elements contributing to the success of Hong Kong," he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
"In seeking reforms, we will do so step by step paying due
attention to the need to maintain the community's prosperity and
stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Depending on the individual circumstances, we will introduce
reforms in different areas at varying speeds and by different
means," said Tung, expressing his confidence that a better society
will be built in Hong Kong by implementing the reforms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
