<HEADLINE> Boeing Unveils Program Focus On Leasing, Maintenance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Boeing Co., the world's
largest airplane maker, said Tuesday it has unveiled a new program
to lease commercial jets to airlines and provide maintenance
services, adding the new program will ultimately bring in revenues
rivaling those on commercial jet sales.
</P>
<P>
"You'll see us being a very active participant in the growth of
Boeing," said Joe Gullion, president of Boeing's airplane services
group, noting that more than 10,000 Boeing planes now in use are
candidates for maintenance contracts.
</P>
<P>
The lease and maintenance schemes will focus first on used
airplanes but eventually will include new planes, according to
Gullion, who declined to predict how big the maintenance program
might become.
</P>
<P>
However, he compared it to General Electric Co.'s jet engine
business, where he said services account for 85 percent of the
revenues compared to 15 percent from engine sales alone.
</P>
<P>
Boeing Tuesday announced that DHL Worldwide, a global express
carrier, would lease 44 757-freighters from Boeing over 15 years
for 1.3 billion U.S. dollars and pay Boeing an undisclosed sum to
maintain the planes, including spare parts management, record-
keeping and engineering services.
</P>
<P>
Of the 44 757s that Boeing will lease to DHL Worldwide, 34 will
come from British Airways Plc's inventory, as the flagship British
carrier prepares to place an order for smaller jets.
</P>
<P>
Boeing will spend between 7 million to 9 million dollars each
to convert those 757s, which carry between 200-240 passengers,
into freighters and will deliver them to DHL Worldwide, plus
another 10 converted 757s yet to be identified by November 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
