<HEADLINE> 13 Former Egyptian Ministers to Remain in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Prime Minister-designate
Atef Ebeid will likely ask at least 13 of the 32 ministers of the
former government to remain in office, the national daily Al
Gomhuria reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The ministers of defense, information, foreign affairs, health,
environment and culture of the outgoing Prime Minister Kamal
El-Ganzouri's cabinet are widely believed to retain their posts,
said the pro-government newspaper, which usually reflects the
thinking of the leadership.
</P>
<P>
After he was sworn in on Tuesday for a fourth consecutive
six-year term in office, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak chose
Ebeid to form the new government. Ebeid is expected to submit to
Mubarak a list of cabinet ministers on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ebeid, former public business sector minister of El-Ganzouri's
cabinet, is in charge of the country's privatization program. His
appointment shows Mubarak's determination and commitment to
further carrying out the economic reform programs beginning in
1991, which have significantly boosted the opening and
diversification of Egypt's economy.
</P>
<P>
The report of the Arabic-language paper said Egypt will, for
the first time, create a new cabinet post, the ministry of
technology, to be in charge of the country's scientific and
technological development.
</P>
<P>
Hasham el-Sherif, former chief of the Cabinet Information
Center, is said to have been nominated for the post, it added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, officials including Hitler Tantawi, chief of the
Administrative Monitoring Agency, Ahmed Fadel, chairman of the
Suez Canal Authority, Hussein Ramzi Kazem, governor of Sharkia
Governorate and Ali Eddin Helal, dean of Cairo University's
Faculty of Economics and Political Sciences have been chosen to
take cabinet posts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
