<HEADLINE> Zambia Calls for Probe in Congo Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba has urged the Joint Military Commission (JMC) to start
work immediately to check the reported escalating skirmishes in
the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Chiluba made the appeal upon his return here Tuesday from the
third Southern Africa International Dialogue held in Victoria
Fall, Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's Daily Mail quoted him as saying that the JMC, which
was set up to verify the implementation of the ceasefire agreement
signed in Lusaka in July to end the year-long DRC conflict, should
start meeting to detect the reported fighting areas.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba, a major ceasefire broker of the DRC conflict,
condemned the reported breakout of fighting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile rebel leader Wamba Dia Wamba backed by Uganda was
quoted as saying that the fighting was still going on in some
parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
He called for concerted efforts by the regional powers to end
the war in the third largest African country. 
</P>
