<HEADLINE> Security to Be Briefed Up at Foreign Embassies in Bangkok </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government will step up
security measures outside all foreign embassies here, following
the seizure of Myanmar's embassy to Thailand by five armed
Myanmese students last Friday, the Thai News Agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Prime Minister and Interior Minister Sanan
Kachornprasart was quoted as saying on Wednesday that the police
were instructed to increase their presence outside all the
diplomatic missions; while inside, the foreign embassies were
responsible for arranging and managing their own security
measures.
</P>
<P>
Security procedures at Maneeloy Holding Center for Myanmese
refugees in the province of Rachaburi would also be reviewed, as
two of the five armed Myanmese students, who held 96 people as
hostages, came from the center, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Thai and Myanmese governments have agreed to
exchange information to help strengthen security procedures at
their embassies in the other country.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached during a meeting between Thai Foreign
Minister Surin Pitsuwan and his Myanmese counterpart Win Aung
early this week in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Surin said that Mr. Win Aung expressed his satisfaction that
the incident was resolved peacefully. 
</P>
</TEXT>
