<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Loses 9.7 Billion Dollars in 1995/96 Fiscal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Public Accounts
Committee has revealed that the government lost a total amount of
580 billion shillings (9.7 billion U.S. dollars) in the 1995/96
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
Public Accounts Committee Chairman Henry Obwocha Tuesday told
the parliament that the Finance Ministry lost 515 billion
shillings while the Office of the President lost four billion.
</P>
<P>
Obwocha published the shocking statistics when he tabled a
summary document on the plunder of public funds and general
financial indiscipline that pervaded the public sector, local
press reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The losses also included 9.3 billion shillings by the Central
Bank, 9.6 billion shillings by the defunct Kenya Post and
Telecommunications Corporation and Kenya Railways and other state
corporations.
</P>
<P>
However, Speaker Francis ole Kaparo rejected the document as
unprocedural and out of order.
</P>
<P>
Kaparo said the summary could be legally interpreted to be
Obwocha's own work and not that of the committee, which compiled
it after 69 sittings beginning last August. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
