<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tung: Top Priority Given to Protection of Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong Chief Executive Tung
Chee Hwa stressed that top priorities should be given to dealing
with air and water pollution and environmental protection in the
coming years.
</P>
<P>
Tung made the remarks in his third policy address to the
Legislative Council here Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
With the theme of "fostering quality people and beautifying our

homes", the policy address is mainly about education, health,
urban
construction and environment, but the focus is on the environment.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive devoted much of his speech to tackling the
air and
water pollution and protection of the environment. He also drew
the
blueprints for improvement of air quality, sewage disposal and
solid
waste recycling in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
In his seven-part speech, Tung said that looking back on the
past two years, Hong Kong has experienced two momentous changes.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's reunification with the mainland following the end
of colonial rule and the practice of a high degree of autonomy
under the unprecedented "One Country, Two Systems" concept, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that the considerable readjustment to Hong Kong's
economy was triggered by the regional and even global effects of
the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
In the first part of his speech, Tung emphasized the importance
of education among the young generations and health care for the
elderly and the youth, while in the later part of the speech he
stressed the necessities of institutional reforms and building a
caring, decent society with a rich cultural life.
</P>
<P>
To achieve even greater success in the next century, Hong Kong
must not only have people of high caliber and a quality
environment, but also sound institutions and a basic structure
which is conductive to economic prosperity, he concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
