<HEADLINE> HK Chief Executive Presents 1999 Policy Address </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR), delivered
his Policy Address of 1999 at the Legislative Council here
Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
This is Tung's third policy address since he became the SAR
chief executive in mid-1997 when Hong Kong returned to China.
</P>
<P>
This year's address is mainly about the economy and education,
but the focus is on education and training of young generations.
</P>
<P>
"Within a hundred days, we will enter the new century and the
new millennium, and Now it is time that we should carry out what
we have achieved and to task the new course to the new century,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
In his policy address, Tung reviewed Hong Kong's development
since its unification with China and pictured the way forward to
the next century to build Hong Kong into a knowledge based center.
</P>
<P>
Before spelling out the new policies, Tung looked back to the
past two years, saying that Hong Kong has experienced two
tremendous changes: the unification with the motherland and the
economic adjustment.
</P>
<P>
Taking Hong Kong into the new millennium, the chief executive
devoted the first part of his speech to taking stock of the policy
programs in his two previous blueprints and consolidating his
plans for the SAR.
</P>
<P>
Last year's priorities were strategies of innovation and
technological development, labor and employment, economic
development, and land and housing.
</P>
<P>
Immediately after the delivery, Tung will give a press
conference for local and foreign reporters, detailing the main
points of the plans and programs.
</P>
<P>
Tung's speech goes live not only on the local radio and
television but also globally via the Internet starting at 2:30
p.m. local time (0630 GMT)  
</P>
</TEXT>
