<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 07:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Israel's Beaches Polluted by Heavy Metal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Israel's beaches have been
contaminated by a large amount of heavy metal carried here by
wind from Europe and some of the metal is considered toxic and
with nitrates used in fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
This was disclosed in a comprehensive report on the sate of
Mediterranean beaches in 1998 published this week by the
Institute of Oceanographic and Limnological Research of Israel.
</P>
<P>
Researchers conducted test on dust particles on the beaches and
found that the contaminants were carried to Israel by dust
particles from Europe and some of them came down with the rain.
</P>
<P>
Nitrogen and ammonia also made their way here from Europe
and the source of those elements was fuel combustion and animal
waste, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report said that compared to rivers in other
places in the world, Israel's rivers have been polluted with
fertilizers to a considerably higher degree. This is because of
the small amount of water flowing in the rivers and large amount
of sewage poured into them.
</P>
<P>
The experts at the institute expressed fear that if the sewage
from the rivers reaches the sea, the sea may be contaminated with
fecal bacteria.
</P>
<P>
The main danger posted by the high concentration of
fertilizers is that they lead to the development of plant life
some of which is toxic. In Haifa Bay, the report said, irregular
amount of water plants, some toxic, have developed because of the
pollution.
</P>
<P>
Heavy metal tests on fish have shown that all the fish are
edible, although the report does mention a number of severe
problems of pollution of beaches caused by mercury.
</P>
<P>
High mercury levels have been found in Haifa Bay and the
main source of this pollution is the Haifa sewage treatment
plant and Haifa Chemicals, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
