<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya to Offer 49 Percent of Telkom to Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government is
prepared to offer 49 percent of Telkom Kenya to a foreign
investor, Kenya's Daily Nation newspaper said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This came after its initial offer of a 26 percent stake in the
telecom firm met little foreign interest, officials said Tuesday,
adding that even this may not be enough to attract a bid.
</P>
<P>
Some prospective strategic investors had strongly demanded an
option to increase their stake to a controlling 51 percent in the
coming years, they added.
</P>
<P>
Privatizing Kenya's dilapidated telecommunications industry is
seen by the World Bank as a major test of the government's
commitment to its privatization process, and would help propel the
stalled talks between Western donors and Kenya over the suspended
loans.
</P>
<P>
However, ceding a controlling interest to foreigners is a
political sensitive issue.
</P>
<P>
The government had originally proposed selling 26 percent to a
foreign investor, to be followed by the sale of 20 percent to the
public through a share offer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
