<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 07:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Tax Revenues Below July Peak in September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Israel's tax revenues in
September totaled 2.8 billion U.S. dollars, compared with 2.75
billion U.S. dollars in August and 2.9 billion U.S. dollars in
July, according to figures published Wednesday by the Finance
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
For the first nine months of the year, revenues totaled 23.6
billion U.S. dollars, compared with 21.85 billion U.S. Dollars
during the same period of 1998. After adjusting for inflation,
this was a real increase of only 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said the tax revenues failed to rise
significantly in September and the tax collection in the month
may had been affected by the shortage of working days due to too
many holidays.
</P>
<P>
For the first nine months of the year, income and real estate
tax revenues totaled 12.97 billion U.S. dollars. In real terms,
this was identical to the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Customs and Value Added Taxes (VAT) revenues totaled 10.07
billion U.S. dollars during the first nine months of 1999, a real
increase of 4.3 percent over the same period last year. This
included a 3.3 percent rise in VAT revenues and a 8.5 percent
increase in import tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also reported a drop in imports of durable
goods in September in almost every category.
</P>
<P>
For the first nine months period as a whole, the ministry
said, imports of most durable goods rose, but car imports were
the exception. 
</P>
</TEXT>
