<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Apple Unveils New iMac Computers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Apple Computer Inc. Tuesday
unveiled an even more sophisticated version of its highly
successful iMac computers, introducing machines with features
never before seen on a personal computer, according to reports
from the company.
</P>
<P>
The new iMac is slightly smaller than its best-selling
predecessor. The machine, which begins shipping immediately, runs
at 350 megahertz and retails for 999 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Extending the iMac family line, Apple also is selling the iMac
DV, a 400MHz, 1,299 dollar model that lets users play and edit DVD
movies, and a special-edition machine for 1,499 dollars that comes
in a clear gray color and is more powerful.
</P>
<P>
Apple interim Chief Executive Steve Jobs said the new basic
model should help Apple make further inroads with first-time
computer buyers seeking a cheap way to get connected to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
Computer buyers who enroll for three years on CompuServe's
Internet service also receive an additional 400 dollars off any
Apple product.
</P>
<P>
Apple is hoping the added features prove more attractive than
sub-1,000 dollar offerings from such competitors as Compaq and
Hewlett-Packard, said Mitch Mandrich, the company's vice president
of worldwide sales.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts generally cheered the new Apple machines as
one of the company's strongest product launches to date.
</P>
<P>
Aside from the added video features and improved speed, memory
and audio performance of the latest iMac, the new machines look
essentially like the original iMac, which was introduced 13 months
ago, drawing overwhelming demand.
</P>
<P>
Apple Tuesday also unveiled a sixth color, graphite, for those
with more subdued tastes. The graphite color will be offered
exclusively on the new iMac DV Special Edition, which contains
extra storage and memory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
