<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Govt, Rebels Move to Cease Fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government and the
Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF) on Wednesday gave separate
orders to their respective troops to cease fighting to ensure the
opening of their formal peace talks scheduled for October 25.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Jarry Barican said in a press statement
that Defense Undersecretary Orlando Soriano, chairman of the
government peace panel, and Gadzali Jaafar, MILF vice chairman for
political affairs, agreed Tuesday after meeting in the southern
province of Maguindanao to diffuse the situation in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
"As of 10 a.m. today, both the military and the MILF troops had
been given specific orders to cease and desist from any further
fighting on the ground," Barican said in the statement read for
him by Deputy Presidential spokesman Angelico Salud.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, Soriano and Jaafar also agreed to
meet again Wednesday afternoon to undertake all measures necessary
to ensure the opening of the formal peace talks between the two
sides due to open on October 25.
</P>
<P>
The 10-day heavy fighting between the government troops and the
MILF guerrillas in various parts of Central Mindanao has
reportedly claimed the lives of 67 rebels and 9 government
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the MILF declared it will withdraw from the peace
talks if the government troops continue to attack the guerrillas'
camps.
</P>
<P>
The fighting broke out on September 26 when some 100 MILF
rebels attacked a military installation in Shariff Aguak,
Maguindanao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
