<HEADLINE> ADB Approves 130 Million U.S. Dollar Loan To </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The African Development Bank
(ADB) has approved the release of 130 million U.S. dollars to
support Zimbabwe's economic reform program.
</P>
<P>
An official in the office of the ADB Executive Director for
Zimbabwe in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, told The Herald daily that an
agreement for the release of the funds was signed on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Obert Matshalaga, director for domestic and international
finance of Zimbabwe's Ministry of Finance, signed the document
with Cyril Enweze, ADB vice-president for operations.
</P>
<P>
The money would be released in three tranches, with the first
tranche of 45 million U.S. dollars expected soon, the official in
Abidjan said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB's funds would surely help revive Zimbabwe's economy
following the approval of the193 million U.S. dollars stand-by
credit for the country by the International Monetary Fund (IMF) on
August 2 this year.
</P>
<P>
However, there were fears that Zimbabwe could fail to get
further financial aid from the IMF and the World Bank following
allegations of conflicting figures on the country's military
expenditure in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa has denied
misleading the IMF and said he had clarified the issue with the
IMF and the World Bank in Washington last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
