<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 07:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE to Issue Law Combating Money Laundering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates
(UAE) will soon issue a federal law to make money laundering a
crime, the local daily Gulf News reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A committee comprising officials from the Central Bank and the
ministries of finance and industry, the interior and justice have
already prepared a draft legislation in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The law, once approved, will define different crimes related
to money laundering and impose penalties and punishments
accordingly, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
At present money laundering-related crimes are being tackled
with directives issued by the UAE Central Bank and the ministries
concerned.
</P>
<P>
According to Central Bank officials, the UAE is vulnerable to
illegal financial activities because it is an excellent and
important commercial center with a very open market policy in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the UAE boasts of a stable currency without high
inflation. People can bring in and out as much as, and whatever,
currency they want.
</P>
<P>
All these factors contributed to attracting money launderers
to the UAE. Therefore, stricter policies and more cooperation
with international bodies are required to protect the country's
reputation, the officials stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Technology Fair Attracting International Businesses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shenzhen, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Technolgy Fair,
which opened here Tuesday, has attracted more than 50
multinationals and many international risk capital investors.
</P>
<P>
The fair's theme is "International Computer, Telecoms, and
Internet Products" and participants say they are optimistic about
the future of China's hi-tech industrial development and its
market potential.
</P>
<P>
A representative of Lucent China Ltd. said that the company's
headquarters in the U.S. has paid a great deal of attention to the
fair and sent seven CEOs and more than 200 personnel to display
their latest Wide Band products.
</P>
<P>
International giants like Microsoft, IBM, and Ericsson also
have eye-catching displays showing their latest technology and
products. One official pointed to the rapid development in China's
information industry and its estimated annual sales worth 18.700
billion U.S. dollars. China has become Ericsson's largest market,
with 12 percent of its total sales worldwide.
</P>
<P>
More than 955 investors are looking at projects, 125 of them
from outside China. They include risk capital investors like the U.
S.'s Boston Investment Bank and IDG Technology Investment Bank.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Ziqing, the director of the Shenzhen Guanri Hi-Tech Co.
Ltd., says that they signed a contract worth 40 million U.S.
dollars with IDG to develop hi-tech telecoms products with an
initial investment of 26 million dollars from IDG at the beginning
of this year.
</P>
<P>
Risk capital investment analysts say that now is a crucial time
for reforming China's technology research, meaning a good
opportunity for foreign investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
