<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Asia's Longest Bridge May Be Privatized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Bangabandhu Jamuna Multi-purpose
Bridge, the longest bridge in Bangladesh as well as in South Asia,
is likely to be privatized, The Bangladesh Observer newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The idea of the Jamuna Multi-purpose Bridge Authority (JMBA) is
to go for a corporate restructuring of the bridge by floating its
shares in the stock exchange and as a holding company, the JMBA
may like to retain the majority of the shares.
</P>
<P>
The 4.8-kilometer-long 18.5-meter-wide bridge in Tangail
district, some 70 kilometers northwest of Dhaka, was completed in
June last year and links northwest Bangladesh with the country's
central-eastern region.
</P>
<P>
It is speculated that the JMBA would float shares of 5 billion
to 6 billion taka (100 million to 120 million U.S. dollars) in the
share market after forming a public limited company to raise its
capital which is expected to be used to maintain the bridge and to
develop other infrastructures of the country.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, the JMBA invited scaled tender from local
chartered accountancy firms registered under the Chartered
Accountancy Act to make a feasibility study, and the authority
received three scaled tender proposals within the stipulated
period.
</P>
<P>
Sources were quoted as saying that all the three tender
proposals with recommendations from the evaluation committee of
the project have been sent to the JMBA board headed by the
communication minister, and the next procedure of privatizing the
bridge would start after getting the board's approval on the
recommendations by the evaluation committee.
</P>
<P>
A JMBA source said the procedure of privatizing the 900
million-dollar bridge would begin with an extensive feasibly study
by local chartered accountancy firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
