<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Migrants Remit 990 Million Dollars in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Around 350,000 Nepali migrant
workers working in different parts of the world send up to 69
billion rupees (990 million U.S. dollars) home in 1996-97 fiscal
year, The Kathmandu Post quoted a report Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This figure accounts for over 25 percent of the Gross Domestic
Product of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The preliminary report "Foreign labor migration and remittance
economy of Nepal", released Tuesday by Department for
International Development, a British development agency, put the
number of Nepali migrant workers in Western Europe and other
western countries at 15,000; in the Gulf at 40,000; in the Far
East at 44,000; in India at over 250,000 and in other parts of the
world at around 1,000.
</P>
<P>
According to the report's "conservative estimate" for 1997, a
total of around 12,500 Nepalese work in Europe and perhaps as many
as 2,500 in North America. Britain has the largest number for a
single country, where 3,600 are officially registered and an
estimated 8,000 more work unofficially.
</P>
<P>
The report has broadly classified four regions where Nepali
migrants find employment - the West (Europe and North America);
the Far East and South East Asia, the Gulf; and India. Only a
small number of Nepalese are employed outside these four regions.
</P>
<P>
The smallest numbers are to be found in the first region and
many Nepalese living and working in this region do not send
remittances back home, particularly in North America where many
people are working as professionals, often accompanied by their
families.
</P>
<P>
"We have estimated that the European migrants alone sent back
around 4.4 billion rupees (63 million U.S. dollars) in 1997. From
North America we estimated a total of some 50 million rupees
(720,000 U.S. dollars)," said the report.
</P>
<P>
The second smallest number of Nepali workers in 1997 were in
the Gulf where a total of 40,000 Nepalese are employed. They sent
an estimated 1.5 billion rupees (22 million U.S. dollars). The
number, which increased dramatically since 1997, may now be about
90,000.
</P>
<P>
The region from which the great majority of remittance come
into Nepal is East and South East Asia where at least 44,000
Nepalese are employed, over half of whom are working illegally. In
Japan, an estimated 10,000 migrants are said to be illegal. A
conservative estimate produces a total of around 23 billion rupees
(330 million U.S. dollars) in remittances from this region.
</P>
<P>
Of this the majority comes from Hong Kong with 14.4 billion
rupees (210 million U.S. dollars); 6 billion rupees (86 million
U.S. dollars) from Japan: one billion rupees (15 million U.S.
dollars) from Brunei and Singapore respectively.
</P>
<P>
Other countries and regions where Nepalese are employed include
Spain, South Korea, Taiwan, Thailand, Malaysia, the Maldives and
the Philippines. Of these countries and regions, the highest
remittance comes from South Korea with 256 million rupees (3.7
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
In terms of absolute monetary value, India provides the largest
share with 40 billion rupees (580 million U.S. dollars),
accounting for 33 percent of total remittances.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the official number of those living
and working abroad increased during the 1980's, from around
400,000 in 1981 to around 660,000 by 1991. This constituted about
3.3 percent of the Nepal's population, and over 10 percent of the
economically active population. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Top Guerrillas Killed in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Three top ultra-leftist
guerrillas were killed in a clash with police in Mahat VDC of
Rukum district in Mid-western Nepal Sunday night, the Kathmandu
Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to police sources, the guerrillas killed in the
encounter were probably of the "A" class, mainly the top class of
the guerrilla. But the sources did not disclose the names of the
killed.
</P>
<P>
The guerrilla killed eight policemen and one local politician
and injured dozens of others in attacks against police posts on
September 22 in Rukum and Jajarkot districts in mid-western Nepal,
which are the base of the guerrilla activities.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile a series of blasts by the guerrilla were reported in
various parts of the country since September. The objectives were
mainly government buildings and police posts. A students bus and a
factory were also targeted in recent blasts. No one was reported
hurt in the blasts.
</P>
<P>
A total of 945 persons have lost their lives since the
guerrilla launched their People's War in 1996. Among them, 158
were civilians, 81 were policemen and 706 were guerrilla members.
</P>
</TEXT>
