<HEADLINE> SAID Delegates Agree to Get Down to Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Delegates at the third Southern
Africa International Dialogue (SAID) ended their deliberations in
Zimbabwe's Victoria Falls Tuesday with an undertaking to get down
to business and implement resolutions reached at the conference,
the daily Herald reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The delegates said that in the past there had been a culture of
 convening conferences and formulating ideas but these would not
be followed up on.
</P>
<P>
Winding up the plenary session, Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe said the conference had proposed the setting up of a number
of projects to create jobs in the region and programs of action
should be put in place immediately.
</P>
<P>
"Several business projects, such as regional tourism, have been
 identified as having immediate and great potential," Mugabe
said.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue also resolved to include first ladies to lead
discussion of social issues in the Smart Partnership process.
</P>
<P>
Summing up the first ladies' discussions, Zimbabwe's First Lady
Grace Mugabe said they noted that there was need for greater
commitment to fighting AIDS, the street children problem,
empowering women and removing laws that discriminated against
them.
</P>
<P>
The delegates also agreed to embrace the media as a critical
partner in the dialogue process, with special emphasis on
developing closer links and meeting regularly.
</P>
<P>
The three-day SAID '99 was attended by about 400 delegates
including 11 heads of state and government, business and labour
representatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
