<HEADLINE> Leading Computer Maker Offers Low-cost Workstation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Sun Microsystems Inc., the
leading maker of computers used to run the Internet, cut the price
Tuesday on its Ultra 5 Unix-based workstation to under 2,000
dollars, putting the machines within the range of personal
computer prices, according to a report from the company.
</P>
<P>
"The move toward the network services model has created a
tremendous need for low-cost, reliable Unix development platforms,
" said Ken Okin, Sun's vice president and general manager of
workstation products.
</P>
<P>
"Providing access to multiple operating environments on one
system benefits our customers in the application development
market," he added.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the Palo Alto, a California-based computer
maker, said it had cut the price of its Ultra 5 Unix workstation
by 20 percent to 1,995 dollars, the first Unix workstation under 2,
000 dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Ultra 5 runs six software operating systems in one
workstation: Sun's own Solaris, Java, which it pioneered,
Microsoft Corp.'s Windows NT, Windows 95, DOS and open-source
Linux, the statement added. 
</P>
