<HEADLINE> U.S. House Approves Foreign Aid Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives Tuesday approved a foreign aid bill that will
reduce the country's foreign aid funding.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton, who last week promised to relieve 1
billion U.S. dollars in debt owed by the poorest countries, has
indicated that his administration will veto the bill.
</P>
<P>
The bill offers "woefully inadequate" funding for foreign aid,
Clinton said in a letter to House Speaker Dennis Hastert on
September 30.
</P>
<P>
Democrats in the House complain that the bill does not match
the "leadership role" of the United States in the world, while
Republicans say there isn't any more money for foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
An earlier version of the legislation, which was compromised by
the House and Senate negotiators, was approved by a vote of 214-
211 on a partisan line.
</P>
<P>
The new bill eliminates 241 million U.S. dollars for a program
to assist former Soviet Union nuclear weapons scientists, and sets
aside 12.62 billion U.S. dollars in foreign spending for the
fiscal year 2000, nearly 2 billion U.S. dollars less than the
president had requested.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration had vetoed the earlier version
approved by Congress because an anti-abortion provision was
appended to the legislation, prohibiting U.S. funds from flowing
into international family planning institutions that back abortion.
</P>
<P>
That provision was also eliminated in the new version. But
Clinton has still vowed to veto it, because of the "woefully
inadequate" funding for foreign aid. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Asks UN to Set up E. Timor Peace-Keeping Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Wednesday asked
the United Nations to set up a proper peace-keeping force for East
Timor immediately in place of the Australia-led international
force for East Timor (Interfet).
</P>
<P>
Interfet was formed because the UN decision-making process on
the peace-keeping force was very slow, Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said Wednesday at an airport press conference in
Subang near here on his returning from a two-week working visit to
New York, London and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
At the moment it is not really a peace-keeping force, it is a
temporary measure initiated by Australia mainly, but the United
Nations has sanctioned it, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir said Malaysia was prepared to send a large military
contingent there to serve with the proposed UN peace-keeping force
"without any problem".
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has a 30-member complement in Interfet, led by a
brigadier- general. 
</P>
