<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian New House Speaker Sworn in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Akbar Tandjung, new Speaker of
Indonesia's House of Representatives (DPR), was sworn in here
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Four new vice-speakers of the DPR were also sworn in
simultaneously. They are A.M. Fatwa (chairman of the National
Mandate Party), Soetardjo Soerjogoeritno (chairman of the
Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle), Khofifah Indarparawansa
(chairman of the National Awakening Party) and Hamzah Haz (general
chairman of the United Development Party).
</P>
<P>
The new House speaker was elected following an acrimonious
debate over technicalities.
</P>
<P>
The debate, which went beyond midnight Tuesday, surfaced when
Crescent Star Party legislator Hartono Mardjono protested the
result of a consultative meeting which unanimously appointed Akbar
to the House's top post.
</P>
<P>
His objection came just after interim speaker Abdul Madjid
praised the result of the consultative meeting attended by
representatives of the House's 10 factions.
</P>
<P>
Citing the House's internal rules, Hartono said the decision
was not binding because the rules grant individual House
legislators the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
The new DPR was forced to vote to elect its speaker, and Akbar
won the voting with 411 votes.
</P>
<P>
The DPR has a total of 500 members who serve for five years. It
exercises legislative authority, with 462 members directly elected
and 38 reserved for the Military/National Police whose members do
not vote.
</P>
<P>
A total of 21 of the 48 political parties which contested the
June 7 general election gained seats in the DPR.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian Democratic Party of Struggle won the election
with 153 seats. The Golkar Party came in second with 120 seats,
followed by the United Development Party, the National Awakening
Party, the National Mandate Party, the Crescent Star Party and the
Justice Party.
</P>
<P>
The DPR meets at least once a year. All laws must have the
approval of the DPR, but the president has absolute veto. Members
of the DPR have the right to submit draft bills which require
ratification by the president. The president may enact ordinance
in times of emergency, which however must be either ratified or
revoked by the DPR at its following session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
