<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Money Laundering Charges Filed in Bank of New York Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Federal District Court
indicted three people and three companies on criminal charges
Tuesday in the Bank of New York probe which alleges the laundering
of 7 billion U.S. dollars from Russia.
</P>
<P>
Peter Berlin, Lucy Edwards and Aleksey Volkov as well as Benex
International Co. Inc., Becs International L.L.C. and Torfinex
Corp. were named as the defendants. They are charged with
illegally funneling large amounts of money into the United States
through the bank from 1996 to August 1999.
</P>
<P>
The three-count indictment was filed under seal in U.S.
District Court on September 16. The charges are the first to
result from an investigation by federal prosecutors in New York
city.
</P>
<P>
Berlin was president of Both Benex and Becs, while his wife
Edwards was vice president in the Eastern European Division at the
Bank of New York and also an officer of Benex and Becs.
</P>
<P>
The indictment alleges that the defendants sent money
illegally through the Benex and Becs account at the bank; the
money was reportedly transmitted by Torfinex Corp. Prosecutors did
not disclose the role Volkov, president of Torfinex, played in the
money laundering.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Attorney Mary Jo While said, "The ongoing investigation
is very intense and broad," adding "it is likely to go on for some
time."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
