<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Warns Against Adverse Effects on Relations with Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar has warned that the
recent siege of Myanmar Embassy in Bangkok by Myanmar armed men
could bring about some adverse effects on the bilateral relations
between Thailand and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
In its editorial, the official newspaper The New Light of
Myanmar said Wednesday that the incident is the second major
lawless and untoward one to have occurred on the Thai soil.
</P>
<P>
"So it is time for Thailand, which has to shoulder the
responsibility, to stop and think that this could very well lead
to some adverse effects on bilateral relations between Thailand
and Myanmar," the paper warned.
</P>
<P>
The paper charged that the acts, perpetrated by "terrorists",
all originated from Thailand as their base of operations.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that at the Thai-Myanmar border, there are 24
camps officially recognized as refugee camps, saying that these
camps are historically linked with acts of "terrorism".
</P>
<P>
"Armed terrorist groups, under the mask of democracy, are using
armed force and violence which no government in the world can
accept or tolerate, and are launching their operations from places
inaccessible to the Myanmar government," it stated.
</P>
<P>
It blamed that most of these camps are simply providing shelter
to a variety of armed insurgents and their families, adding that
those who always cross over the border to attack Myanmar, come
from nowhere else, but these camps.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Thai Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai's remarks
carried on the October 3 issue of "the Nation" newspaper of
Thailand as saying that "It is necessary to keep a stricter and
closer watch on the opposition activities of expatriate Myanmar
students against the Myanmar government".
</P>
<P>
Five armed men, who are all Myanmar students living in
Thailand, seized the Myanmar Embassy in Bangkok on last Friday
morning and held the embassy staff together with some foreigners
as hostages.
</P>
<P>
The incident ended peacefully on the next day afternoon with
all the 38 hostages freed before the armed men were flown out of
the embassy compound to the Thai-Myanmar border area with two
helicopters provided by the Thai authorities after negotiation
between them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
