<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diesel Prices Hike in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Government Tuesday night
announced an unprecedented 40 percent hike in diesel prices.
</P>
<P>
The new prices, which come into effect from Wednesday, will
partially neutralize the 60 percent increase in international
prices of diesel recorded over the last six months.
</P>
<P>
The basic price of diesel has been raised from 6.88 rupees
(0.16 U.S. dollar) per liter to 9.63 rupees (0.22 U.S. dollar) per
liter. But with taxes, the rates will go up further.
</P>
<P>
While the timing of the price hike may have seemed some what
unusual, senior officials of the Oil Coordination Committee (OCC)
said diesel prices should have been raised three months ago.
</P>
<P>
The decision had been postponed in view of the Petroleum
Ministry's view that the price fluctuation should be watched for
some time.
</P>
<P>
OCC officials claimed the issue of diesel prices had not been
raised in Wednesday's Cabinet meeting since increase of this
product can now be carried out by the Ministry under the new
liberalized policy regime.
</P>
<P>
The hike in prices will yield as much as 66 billion rupees
(1.53 billion U.S. dollars) to the exchequer and enable the OCC to
draw down the oil pool account deficit by this amount during the
current fiscal.
</P>
<P>
According to OCC officials, the pool account deficit will have
otherwise risen to 100 billion rupees (2.33 billion U.S. dollars)
by March next year. As a result of the price hike, the deficit
will be contained to 34 billion rupees (790.70 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
But unless prices of other products like LPG and kerosene are
raised, officials said that the deficit cannot be wiped out and
payments to the oil companies will be deferred. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
