<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Decision to Quit Asiad Bid Hailed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- An official of the Indonesian
Olympics Committee (KONI) hailed the government's decision to
withdraw from its planned bid to host the 2006 Asian Games as a "
sensible retreat".
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia must show the spirit of brotherhood with an ASEAN (
Association of Southeast Asian Nations) country, which is seeking
the chance of becoming the host of the Asian Games," Arie Sudewo
was quoted by the Indonesian Observer Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Sudewo was referring to Malaysia, one of around five candidates
to bid for the hosting of the Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia, which launched its campaign during the 1998 Asian
Games in Bangkok, has looked serious in its aspiration and has
become a strong contender.
</P>
<P>
On the other side, Indonesia which began its own campaign only
recently at the 1999 Brunei Southeast Asian (SEA) Games, has
looked pessimistic and stuttered in its plan, resulting from the
crippling monetary crisis.
</P>
<P>
The "untimely" campaign had drawn controversies given the
current condition that even Minister of Sport and Youth Affairs
Agung Laksono had asked KONI to review the plan.
</P>
<P>
But it was only last week that the government finally settled
to abandon its bid. Relinquishing the campaign, Indonesia has
pledged its support to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is now looking for some kind of pay-off for its
planned support by appealing to Malaysia -- if successful in its
bid -- to include sports which promise medal prospects to
Indonesia such as pencak silat, bridge and chess.
</P>
<P>
Sudewo said that KONI had planned for a delegation to meet the
Malaysian National Olympics Committee to talk over the issue.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia would lobby Asian powers for pencak silat, a
traditional martial art popular in the Southeast Asian region, to
be competed in as an exhibition at the 2002 Asian Games in Pusan,
South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The candidates are to submit their official bidding at the
general assembly meeting of the Asian Olympics Confederation in
Kuwait in November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
