<HEADLINE> Workshop on Drug Law Enforcement Held in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, October 6 (Xinhua) -- A national workshop on narcotic
drug law enforcement is being held here to formulate a CD-ROM
training program compatible with the policies, laws, procedures,
codes and norms being practiced in each six-MOU countries --
China, Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The three-day workshop, which began Tuesday, is sponsored by
Myanmar's Central Committee for Drug Abuse Control (CCDAC) and
the U.N. Drug Control Program.
</P>
<P>
The workshop is conducted as a component of the six-country MOU
sub-regional action plan project on drug law enforcement training
in East Asia agreed by the six countries on July 11, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The training method will eliminate the need to gather drug
enforcement officers to a training center, thereby saving time and
expenses pertaining to travel and undergoing training outside
their duty station, said Major-General Soe Win, secretary of the
Myanmar CCDAC and director-general of the Myanmar Police Force, at
the opening of the workshop.
</P>
<P>
The program, at present, is being formulated by a professional
company and will be translated into appropriate language, he said.
</P>
<P>
A CD-ROM program for drug law enforcement training was first
demonstrated at the six-country MOU meeting in Laos in May this
year and a workshop of national project coordinators, training
experts and international project coordinators was later held in
Bangkok, Thailand, in July.
</P>
<P>
Attending the workshop are officials of the Myanmar Defense
Ministry, CCDAC, Customs Department, Food and Drug Administration
and Myanmar Police Force. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
