<HEADLINE> Nuclear Accident Raises Concerns in S.Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The accident occurred at 7 p.m. local time during a preventive
safety inspection of a water cooling pump of the number three
reactor at the Wolsong nuclear plant, 305 kilometers southeast of
Seoul.
</P>
<P>
The reactor had been out of service since September 23 for
maintenance, the South Korean Science and Technology Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said 45 liters of heavy water contained inside the
reactor leaked, but remained inside the plant and did not pollute
the environment.
</P>
<P>
Those exposed to the radiation were employees of the South
Korean Power Corporation. They were reportedly exposed to levels
far below the limited yearly average of 50mSV, since the nuclear
reactor was not in operation. Nineteen workers returned to work
while another three were prohibited to continue working there.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said a team of nuclear specialists is
investigating the accident.
</P>
<P>
The leak was the smallest of the past four accidents, but it
was the first time that people were reportedly exposed to
radiation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The 700,000-kilowatt number three reactor started commercial
operation last year as South Korea's first pressurized heavy water
reactor, which is modeled after Canada's CANDU reactors.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear leak occurred five days after a disastrous nuclear
accident in Japan in which at least 49 people were exposed to
radiation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam's GDP Expected to Increase 5 Pct This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's GDP is likely to reach
about 390,000 billion Vietnamese dong (28.5 billion U.S. dollars)
this year, a rise of 5 percent over last year, local English daily
Vietnam News Wednesday quoted Vietnam's General Department of
Statistics figures as saying.
</P>
<P>
The forecast was based on the data of the country's economic
performance in the first nine months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The forecast was also judged by economists to be an average
growth rate compared to other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production value is expected to increase 10.5
percent over last year, a lower increase than in past years.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of the industrial production value of the
country was 12 percent in 1998, 13.8 percent in 1997 and 14
percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the first nine months of 1999, the foreign invested sector
of the country reported a rise of more than 19 percent; the
non-state sector nearly 8 percent; and state-owned enterprises 4.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Low-quality, high-priced products unable to compete with
imports because of poor technology were said to be the main cause
for lower growth rates in the state-owned sector.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture, forestry and marine production are expected to
achieve an increase of around 8 percent, while a 2.5 percent rise
is forecast for the service sector.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investment slowed down in the past nine months
though the Vietnamese government has implemented various
encouraging policies. A total of 269 projects worth almost 1.4
billion U.S. dollars in registered capital received licenses
during the period. This marks a 12 percent decrease in the number
of new projects and a 37 percent reduction in registered capital
when compared with the first nine months of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
