<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka, Russia Form Common Front to Combat Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka and Russia will work
hand in hand in the international arena to fight terrorism in the
future, diplomats here said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Russian Ambassador to Sri Lanka Victor Zotin said that
countries like Sri Lanka and Russia should form a common
international front to eradicate the menace of terrorism and the
United Nations could actively participate in this regard.
</P>
<P>
He said Sri Lanka had suffered for the past 16 years in its
fight against separatist Tamil rebels from this scourge which
Russia is facing today.
</P>
<P>
Russia, plagued by recent spate of terrorist bombings which
have so far killed nearly 300 people, blamed the bombings on an
Islamist group in Chechnya in the north Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lankan officials also showed sympathy and understanding to
Russia's situations.
</P>
<P>
"We in Sri Lanka, who are confronted by terrorism, share the
anguish and the pain of the Russian people who are victims of
these atrocities," said Sri Lankan Deputy Minister of Foreign
Affairs Lakshman Kiriella in a letter to his Russian counterpart
Karasin late last month.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the recent incidents of terrorism in the Russian
Federation have highlighted the urgency for greater international
cooperation in combating this menace."
</P>
<P>
Zotin said that foreign countries should not harbor terrorist
organizations nor should they allow terrorists to get involved in
activities to finance their organizations in foreign soils.
</P>
<P>
He added that the world community should stem any separatist
manifestations firmly and consistently to protect the principles
of sovereignty, territorial integrity of states and the
inviolability of borders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
