<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Increases Military Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This is the first time the US has increased its defense
spending since the "cold war" ended.
</P>
<P>
The national defense authorization bill, signed by Clinton
during a special Pentagon visit, includes a 4.8 percent pay raise
for the 1.4 million men and women on active duty, plus a host of
other financial incentives aimed at filling the military ranks.
</P>
<P>
The bill also directs a reorganization of the U.S. Energy
Department to create a largely independent nuclear weapons agency
within the department.
</P>
<P>
The 4.8 percent pay raise is the highest since a 14.3 percent
boost in 1981 during the Reagan administration's military buildup.
The Clinton administration has proposed a 4.4 percent increase for
2000.
</P>
<P>
Clinton was joined in the ceremony by Defense Secretary William
Cohen and the uniformed service chiefs and civilian service
secretaries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the U.S. Defense Department said earlier Tuesday
that the army, navy and marine corps each met their force goals in
the fiscal year that ended last Thursday thanks to anticipated
increases in troops pay and retirement benefits.
</P>
<P>
But the air force, trying to retain and recruit in a booming
civilian market for commercial airline pilots, fell 10,308 short
of its authorized strength of 370,882. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
