<HEADLINE> NATO Clears Highway of Blockade in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, October 5 (Xinhua) -- NATO-led international
peacekeepers in Kosovo (KFOR), with the help of helicopters, tanks
and armored cars, Tuesday cleared road blocks placed by Serbs
along a major highway in Kosovo Polje.
</P>
<P>
KFOR Commander Michael Jackson noted that the troops removed
the roadblocks to keep open the route from Pristina to Pec, a city
in the west of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
But the media said the move indicates the international force
in the province uses double standards because it had not taken
similar actions when ethnic Albanians blocked Russian peacekeepers
in their march into Orahovac in late August.
</P>
<P>
Yugoslav Serbs placed blockade recently along the major highway
to protest a bomb attack on September 28, which killed two people
instantly and injured 36, on a market in Serb-populated Kosovo
Polje. They demanded an explanation from KFOR and the United
Nations mission in Kosovo on the matter.
</P>
<P>
The situation in Kosovo has remained tense as the international
troops and the U.N. mission adopted an approach of appeasement and
nepotism toward Albanian separatists. 
</P>
