<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF to Help Ecuador: President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador's President Jamil Mahuad
Tuesday confirmed that his government and the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) have reached an agreement that will allow
Ecuador to pay only half the interest due on the Brady bonds and
the balance will be borne by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
On September 30, Ecuador became the first country to default on
Brady bonds. Brady bonds, named after former U.S. Treasury
Secretary Nicholas Brady, were created in 1989 to refinance the
debt burden then crushing developing nations. Ecuador's PDI (past
due interest) and discount bonds were issued in 1995 as part of
its Brady Plan to restructure debt.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the agreement with the IMF, the Ecuadorian
president said, in an interview with reporters, that the
international financial organization is very aware of what is
happening to the Ecuadorian economy and thus still willing to help
Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
The agreement will permit the country to collect up to 1.25
billion U.S. dollars of credit to be used in increasing the
foreign currency reserve, updating productive equipment and
performing social projects.
</P>
<P>
However, these credits hinge on the Ecuadorian National
Congress passing the government's budget for the year 2000, in
which there are plans to increase taxes and raise the price of
fuel, which most lawmakers oppose.
</P>
<P>
For this reason, Mahuad has urged the legislators to approve
the budget reforms for the year 2000, and above all, to pass the
planned Value Added Tax (VAT) increases by 10 to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Mahuad is also harboring the hope that he will gain a line of
credit of 900 million U.S. dollars from the Andean Development
Corporation (ADC).
</P>
<P>
Ecuador, in its worst economic crisis in decades, has said it
cannot repay its 13 billion-dollar foreign debt, which takes up
more than half of its budget each year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0292 </DOCNO>
