<HEADLINE> Agassi Wins Opener in Swiss Tennis Indoors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Top-ranked Andre Agassi won his
opener to advance to the second round of the Swiss Indoors in
Basel, Switerland on Tuesday, beating Jan Siemerink of the
Netherlands 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Tim Henman, the defending champion, also booked his
second round berth by beating Swiss wild-card entry George Bastl 7-
5, 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
Agassi, the French and U.S. Open champion, took just 61 minutes
to dispatch Siemerink with his powerful serve from the very
beginning.
</P>
<P>
The loss was another blow to Siemerink, who crashed out in the
opening round for the fourth consecutive year after reaching the
final in 1995.
</P>
<P>
However, Henman, seeking his first title this season, needed
two hours to overcome Bastl.
</P>
<P>
From 2-4 down in the opening set, the fourth-seeded Briton
managed to regain his serve, taking the next three games to go up
5-4 and was overtaken again as Bastl forged ahead 6-5.
</P>
<P>
In the second set, Henman broke the Swiss player's opening
serve to take a 3-0 and recorded three consecutive love service
games before breaking at 5-2 to take the set.
</P>
<P>
He continued to establish his authority in the third, winning
the first eight points in the set to go up 2-0, then jumping to an
insurmountable 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
In other first-round play, Ukraine's Andrei Medvedev, who lost
to Agassi in the French Open final, came back from a one-set
deficit to defeat Russia's Marat Safin 2-6, 6-4, 7-6 (7-2).
</P>
<P>
American qualifier Chris Woodruff upset Austria's Stefan Koubek
3-6, 6-2, 6-2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
