<HEADLINE> Australian Troops Could Be Scaled Back Soon: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- Australia's peacekeeping force
in East Timor could be scaled back in the next two or three
months, Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is certainly the view of the Australian government that we
would like to see the move to the fully fledged United Nations
peacekeeping operation as soon as possible," Downer told ABC
Radio.
</P>
<P>
"It is hard to predict when that will happen but conceivably
that could be in two or three months," he added.
</P>
<P>
Australia now has 3,500 troops in East Timor out of a total
U.N. force of 4,600.
</P>
<P>
AAP said on Wednesday that U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan
has recommended the establishment of a major U.N. military and
civilian operation to shepherd East Timor to independence in two
to three years.
</P>
<P>
He proposed a U.N. Transitional Administration in East Timor to
include almost 9,000 troops with strong powers as well as 200
military observers and more than 1,500 police. 
</P>
