<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Report: Asia Makes Progress in Improving Women Status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, October 6 (Xinhua) -- The Asian financial crisis has
inflicted serious economic pain and suffering on women in terms of
unemployment and loss of pay, but failed to derail their long-term
progress toward greater economic empowerment, an international
organization said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a report released here, the International Labor Office (ILO)
Regional Office for Asia and the Pacific said that although women
suffered disproportionally from the financial crisis, countries in
the region have made "progress toward achieving the goals set out
at the Fourth World Conference on Women in Beijing in September
1995."
</P>
<P>
In some economically and socially advancing countries, the ILO
said, "women have succeeded in gaining greater access to training
and employment and increased economic autonomy and social status."
</P>
<P>
It said that home-based and self-employed women workers in
Thailand have benefited from the establishment of Home Net in
terms of improved labor rights and social protection.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, the ILO said, an integrated plan for gender
and development has resulted in new emphasis on data gathering,
training of women and increased budgeting for gender issues.
</P>
<P>
In Nepal, new efforts to collect data on women's work indicated
a growing acknowledgment of women's economic contribution, it
said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, it said, much remains to be done before realizing
the Beijing Platform for Action's calls for protection and
promotion of women's rights, eradicating poverty, elimination of
violence against women, and promoting their economic autonomy.
</P>
<P>
"A majority of women, such as agricultural laborers, home
workers, traditional artisans, weavers, and vendors... have more
likely been particularly hard hit by the Asian financial crisis,
due to their primary responsibility for providing for their
families' basic needs," said the ILO.
</P>
<P>
It said that the loss of jobs had pushed many women back into
informal sector or agricultural households, where they have had to
cope with less income and higher burdens for themselves, their
children and parents.
</P>
<P>
The ILO called for essential protective legislation in the
region to protect women and girls and strengthen women's status in
the world of work.
</P>
<P>
The ILO report, entitled "Towards Gender Equality in the World
of Work in Asia and the Pacific," was prepared for the Asian
Regional Consultation on Follow-up to the 1995 Fourth World
Conference on Women in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The three-day regional meeting opened here Wednesday morning,
and was being attended by 80 policy-makers, employers and labor
leaders from 24 Asian and Pacific economies.
</P>
<P>
The participants will review country situations and exchange
experiences on gender issues in the world of work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
