<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vessels Traveling on Panama Canal Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The number of vessels
traveling through the Panama Canal rose 1.1 percent in the fiscal
year for 1999 (which ended on September 30), compared with the
same period in 1998, said canal authorities on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 12,201 vessels traveled along the inter-oceanic
canal compared with 12,071 in the prior period, said a statement
from the Panama Canal Commission.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the volume of cargo, the commission said there was
181,111 tons of gross weight, rising 1.8 percent above the 177,892
tons in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Japan, Canada and China are the biggest
users of the canal, according to the commission, and the canal has
an operating capacity of 39 vessels per day, with a maximum
capacity of 42.
</P>
<P>
The canal authorities have predicted that next year would see a
rise in capacity to 44 vessels per day, and a maximum capacity of
55, due to a modernization program started this year.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Torrijos-Carter agreement, signed in
1977 between the former Panamanian President Omar Torrijos and
Jimmy Carter, Panama will take control the Canal on December 31,
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
