<HEADLINE> Vieira Charged by English FA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Arsenal's Patrick Vieira has been
charged with misconduct by the Football Association for "improper
behaviour", which included an alleged spitting incident, during
Sunday's game against West Ham.
</P>
<P>
The French star, who has since apologised, reacted furiously
after he was red-carded by referee Mike Reed in the 84th minute.
</P>
<P>
Television evidence appeared to support Neil Ruddock's claim
that Vieira spat in his face, but Reed said that would not be in
his report because he did not see it.
</P>
<P>
After being dismissed, Vieira returned to argue with referee
Mike Reed and was also involved in an incident with a police
officer in the tunnel at Upton Park.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, the Frenchman said: "My behavior after being sent
off was inexcusable."
</P>
<P>
"Although I was subjected to provocation, I am ashamed of my
action.
</P>
<P>
"Spitting at a fellow professional is something I sincerely
regret. It was a reaction in the heat of the moment and I
apologize to everyone involved in the incident."
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Arsenal said it would take action against the
French international.
</P>
<P>
"Although Patrick Vieira was severely provoked during the game
and at the time of the incident, his response to being sent off
was wrong.
</P>
<P>
"Patrick's reaction was unacceptable and is something that
Arsenal Football Club does not condone. The matter will be
addressed by the Football Association and dealt with internally by
the club."
</P>
<P>
The FA had earlier released a statement which read: "Arsenal's
Patrick Vieira has today been charged with misconduct for improper
behaviour - including alleged spitting - immediately following his
dismissal during yesterday's Premier League game at West Ham.
</P>
<P>
"Vieira has 14 days to respond to the charge and request a
personal hearing if he wishes.
</P>
<P>
"The FA has been informed that a police investigation is being
held into a separate incident in the players' tunnel after Vieira'
s dismissal.
</P>
<P>
"The police have indicated their inquiries will continue until
the end of this week, after which they will forward a report to
the FA for consideration."
</P>
<P>
Vieira hit the headlines last season when he was awarded a then-
record 20,000 pounds fine after his V-sign to the crowd during the
infamous game at Sheffield Wednesday, when Di Canio pushed referee
Paul Alcock to the floor.
</P>
<P>
The Frenchman was also cleared of assaulting a police officer
by an FA disciplinary committee on the same day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
