<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Companies Have Difficulties in Finding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Finding and keeping skilled
workers is the number one issue facing American business today,
according to a survey report released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the report said, more than half of businesses in 11
western and midwestern states said finding and keeping skilled
employees is a bigger issue for them than satisfying or meeting
customer needs, controlling costs or keeping up with competition.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by state-by-state coalitions or business
associations in the 11 states, was released at the International
Telework Association &AMP; Council (ITAC) conference in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
As many as 83 percent of businesses find it somewhat to very
difficult to find people with the skills to do the required work
of a specific job vacancy, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The survey indicates that letting employees work at home --
telework -- is gaining in popularity as one of the best ways to
attract and keep skilled people. In fact, more than three-quarters
of all employees who telework today are happy to have this
employment option.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted ITAC co-chairman Jim Miller as saying that
traffic congestion is not the major reason for telework's
popularity, although it does have the added benefit of reducing
traffic. "It's a lifestyle issue," Miller said, adding that "the
old myth that employees who work at home don't produce as well as
their colleagues back in the office just isn't true according to
data."
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 75 to 95 percent of teleworkers are
satisfied with their remote working option. Company-provided
computer, modem and wireless capability such as cell phones and
pagers are the most popular tools employers provide their
teleworkers.
</P>
<P>
While some companies say they can't let employees telework due
to the nature of their business, other companies in the same
industries are finding ways to allow telework for specific jobs or
tasks, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prodi Urges EU to Set Up Food Safety Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- President of the European
Commission, Romano Prodi, said Tuesday that one way to solve the
crisis of confidence on food safety in the European Union (EU)
could be to set up an independent European Food Agency.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a plenary session of the European Parliament, Prodi
said several EU member states have already taken similar
initiatives by setting up their own independent food safety
authorities. "The idea is that such agencies are more flexible and
better equipped to ensure food safety," he said.
</P>
<P>
"A European Food Agency could, perhaps, be modeled along the
lines of the European Medicines Evaluation Agency (EMEA). This
agency has no decision-making power of its own: it takes purely
technical action but does so with notable swiftness and
efficiency. If anything goes wrong in connection with a drug, the
source of the problem can be traced within hours - whereas in the
case of a food scare it can take weeks," said Prodi who took his
office last month.
</P>
<P>
He also offered the U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) as
"another potential model". The American model with much more
far-reaching powers of decision "would enable action on safety to
be taken very rapidly, independently of the intervention of
political institutions," the president said.
</P>
<P>
"The problem, of course, would be to how ensure democratic
accountability. Nor am I sure that such an agency could be set up
under the Treaty (of Amsterdam)," Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
The new EU executive president also persuaded members of the EU
parliament to choose the alternative for Europe's food safety
mechanism. "I have no preconceived ideas about which model to
follow: I want to listen to your views. The main thing is to get
it right: whichever model we adopt, it must win back citizens'
confidence that their interests are being protected."
</P>
<P>
Noting recent trade disputes with the United States and others,
the president said such disputes have to be settled within the
World Trade Organization (WTO), and EU needs to push for the
establishment of credible international food standards in the
Millennium Round of WTO talks.
</P>
<P>
"Should any conflict arise between consumers' health and
producers' interests, health must take precedence," Prodi
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The food safety issue has worried Europeans for a long time
since discovery of "mad cow" disease in Britain three years ago.
The Europeans has also been scared by dioxin contamination in food
chains and some troubles in soft drinks this year. Therefore,
Prodi said the European Union has on hands "is a major challenge
in ensuring that such crises of confidence are not repeated".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0320 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
