<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Superstar tenor Luciano Pavarotti
was a no-show for the first hearing in his divorce case in his
home town of Modena Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Pavarotti, 63, was engaged on the Australian leg of highly
successful world tour but his long-time wife, Adua Veroni, was in
court on schedule.
</P>
<P>
If Pavarotti had turned up the judge's first move would have
been to try to achieve a reconciliation, as is normal practice
under Italian law.
</P>
<P>
Ms. Veroni is reportedly seeking some 200 billion lire (about
108 million U.S. dollars) from the super-tenor, who recently
settled his account with the German tax man via a hefty fine but
is under investigation in Italy for allegedly conducting the bulk
of his business in Italy while declaring residence in Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
According to Italian news agency Ansa, Pavarotti is offering
considerably less than the sum demanded.
</P>
<P>
When Pavarotti went public on his long-running affair with his
then-26-year-old personal assistant Nicoletta Mantovani in 1996,
the ensuing divorce proceedings were described by both sides as
"amicable".
</P>
<P>
Things appeared to have soured a little since, at least for Ms
Veroni, who like her estranged husband is in her sixties. She was
married to Pavarotti for more than thirty years.
</P>
<P>
Mantovani, who features regularly with her companion in Italy's
most popular magazines, has declared it is her and Pavarotti's
dream to get married. 
</P>
