<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Countries Approve Mechanism to Confront Drugs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The countries of the
Organization of American States (OAS) Tuesday approved the
"Mechanism of Multilateral Evaluation (MEM)" to confront the
trafficking and consumption of drugs.
</P>
<P>
This control mechanism in the fight against drugs was approved
within the frame of the 26th ordinary period of sessions of the
Inter-American Commission for the Control of the Abuse of Drugs
(CICAD) in the OAS.
</P>
<P>
A declaration issued during the meeting, signaled that the
creation of this new mechanism is based on the respect of rights
of sovereignty, territorial jurisdiction and the internal judicial
order of the states, as well as the reciprocity, shared
responsibility, integrity and equilibrium in the treatment of the
issue.
</P>
<P>
The mechanism is applicable to all the states, individually and
collectively and will be governmental, unique and objective with
the participation of specialized representatives of the
governments.
</P>
<P>
It will also exclude sanctions of any nature and respect the
confidentiality of of the deliberations and of the information
received.
</P>
<P>
According to the explanation of the new president of CICAD,
Alberto Scavarelli, the MEM implies that a group of 34 experts
representing each member country of the OAS will elaborate reports
on the anti-drug policies in each of the different countries,
based on 61 indicators.
</P>
<P>
The states will not perform auto-evaluation, but participate in
the reports made by the other states. The MEM establishes that
"all the countries evaluate and they will all be evaluated".
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, there are three thematic fundamental ideas
for the elaboration of the reports from each of the countries: the
reduction of the drugs market (the fight against the drug
trafficking and organized crime), a reduction of the demand
(campaigns of education and rehabilitation) and the international
cooperation performed by each state.
</P>
<P>
Up until now, the U.S. government has performed an evaluation
on a unilateral basis, over the fight against drugs performed by
each of the Latin American countries, and placed sanctions on the
non-approved countries. The actions of the U.S. government were
considered as an intervention of internal matters and strongly
criticized by the countries of the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
