<HEADLINE> PC Magazine Names 100 Most Influential Companies in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft was ranked as
number one among the "100 most influential companies" for the
third consecutive year by PC Magazine in its 1999 analysis of the
U.S. technology industry.
</P>
<P>
America's leading technology magazine said Tuesday that for the
ratings, its editors considered such factors as revenues, market
share, profitability, products performance and subjective
assessments.
</P>
<P>
On the 10 top-ranked list following Microsoft are America
Online, Intel, IBM, Cisco Systems, Amazon.com, Yahoo, Oracle, Dell
and Hewlett-Packard.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the months-long process of developing the list, the
magazine quoted its editor-in-chief Michael Miller as saying that
the huge impact that big Internet firms are having on the
technology industry played a large role.
</P>
<P>
Success in this new era will come to those companies that are
the most effective at producing the hardware, software and
networking infrastructure products and services that get people
online at work and at home and enable them to be productive in
both environments, the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
"Survival of the fittest hinges on a company's ability to adapt
to the Internet, not an ability to withstand it," Miller said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Microsoft as number one, the magazine said that
it continues to set the agenda for personal computing. The
company, which dominates in operating systems and office
applications, has been a strong competitor in providing Internet
service or Internet content.
</P>
<P>
Would Microsoft's influence go down some day? The magazine
quoted Miller as saying: "It seems to me the things that pose the
great threats to Microsoft's influence are the rise of the
Internet as an application platform, the development of many
'appliances' that perform specific functions without the need of
Windows or Microsoft applications, and any restrictions or changes
in the company's business practices that come out of the
Department of Justice antitrust case." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
