<HEADLINE> Italian Premier Pledges Safety for Italian Citizens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 5 (Xinhua) -- In the wake of a recent crime wave
throughout Italy, Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema pledged
that the government would step up crime-fighting measures in a bid
to ensure that Italians once again feel safe in their streets.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the annual assembly of the retailers association,
Confesercenti, the prime minister underlined the fact that
sentences handed out to criminals must be more effective and that
prison terms need to be carried out to the full.
</P>
<P>
D'Alema's comments came in response to public outrage in recent
weeks over crimes committed by persons supposedly under house
arrest or out on parole.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent, much-publicized survey, only about one
fifth of terms are actually served, at the end of a lengthy
process of trial and appeal.
</P>
<P>
Last month, D'Alema pledged that new electronic bracelets for
those under house arrest would be introduced by the end of the
year and said a unified national anti-crime unit would be
operational within six months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
