<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Continue to Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, October 5 (Xinhua) - European stock markets closed
mostly higher Tuesday as investors encouraged by a strong start on
Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 finished higher, up 31.6 points higher at
6084.50, as a sharp drop in leading oil stocks sapped momentum
from the index and left it 20 points off its morning high.
</P>
<P>
Expectations of increased oil exports from Norway and Iraq hit
BP Amoco shares by 19.5p, or 3.4 percent, to 558p and Shell by 7p,
or 1.5 percent, to 459p.
</P>
<P>
A resumption in gold's recent strong price run helped mining
stocks to top the FTSE gainers. Billiton closed 5.5 percent
higher, Rio Tinto added 4.4 percent, and Anglo American was almost
3 percent ahead.
</P>
<P>
Financial stocks also helped to give the FTSE's some forward
momentum. NatWest Group climbed 2.9 percent amid expectations that
a white knight counter-bid may emerge to contest last month's
hostile offer from Bank of Scotland.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax in Frankfurt was Europe's best performer, gaining
82.9 points to close at 5301.85 as deal activity in the telecom
sector sparked investor interest.
</P>
<P>
DaimlerChrysler helped push the market higher, gaining 2.34,
or 3.55 percent, to 68.25 on speculation that the company might
move its headquarter to the US.
</P>
<P>
The CAC 40 index in Paris ended 57.9 points higher at 4661.13
after the monthly consumer confidence survey posted its best
result since 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
