<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Remains Largest Debtor to U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.N. official
Tuesday said that the United States, the richest in the world,
remains the largest debtor to the United Nations by owing the bulk
of the U.N. assessment, which is essential to finance normal
operations of the world body.
</P>
<P>
Joseph Connor, U.N. under-secretary-general for management,
told a press conference here that by September 30, the United
States owed 81 percent of the regular budget aggregate, with two
other principal contributors owing a further 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
By September 30, the United States owed 60 percent of the
peacekeeping assessment, he said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, a non-profit organization, fully relys on
all Member States for financial resources. The U.N. assessment
covers contribution to the regular budget, the peacekeeping and
tribunal assessment.
</P>
<P>
Also Tuesday, the Fifth Committee of the General Assembly
held discussion on the financial situation in the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan told the meeting that "This
committee is central to the administration, financial and
institutional health of this Organization." The Fifth Committee is
in charge of the financial affairs at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
"Without the necessary funding, the United Nations will be
forever handicapped in its ability to fulfill the mandates
entrusted to it by the Member States," he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the U.N. chief called on all Member States to honor
the U.N. Charter and the legal obligation by paying their dues in
full, on time and without any condition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Concerned at Refugees in Russia's Northern  Caucasus Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 5 (xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on Tuesday expressed concern over the humanitarian
situation in the Northern Caucasus region of the Russia
Federation.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General is following closely and with concern
the humanitarian situation in the northern Caucasus region of the
Russian Federation," a statement issued through the U.N. spokesman
said.
</P>
<P>
"According to available estimates, more than 70,000 civilians
have already been displaced, " the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Annan said U.N. agencies were working closely with the Russian
authorities and that three consignments of food and other relief
have already been sent to the region.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations stands ready to cooperate in a rapid
assessment of the humanitarian situation as soon as conditions
permit," the statement added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
