<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0329 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heavy Rains Leave at Least 3 Dead in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, October 5 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican authorities on
Tuesday declared an alert because of the intense rains which have
caused at least three deaths, five injured and 50,000 homeless
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people were displaced on Tuesday, due to rivers in
the Tulancingo region of the state of Hidalgo, in the center of
the country breaking their banks, said authorities from the Civil
Protection.
</P>
<P>
Three people died and five were injured by the collapse of a
marble mine in the municipal of San Salvador in Hidalgo.
</P>
<P>
The National Meteorological Service (SMN) requested the
population to take extreme care because of the intense rains
registered in th coastal region of the Gulf of Mexico, and the
Yucatan Peninsula, as well as the center and southern parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
The authorities in Tabasco said that the state was enduring the
worst rains for forty years, with 50,000 people being affected.
</P>
<P>
In the state of Veracruz in the east of the country, the rains
have caused rivers to break their banks, damaging crops and rural
highways.
</P>
<P>
A total of 800 people have been placed in hostels due to the
inundations in the municipals of Suchiate, Tapachula, Mazatlan and
Acapetahua in the state of Chiapas in the south-east of the
country
</P>
<P>
In Oaxaca, where an earthquake left over 20 dead on September
30, various communities are at present isolated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0330 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Ready to Recognize East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Italy is ready to officially
recognize East Timor as soon as the island sets up a government,
Italian Foreign Undersecretary Valentino Martelli said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Martelli's comments to the Senate were echoed by Senator Giulio
Andreotti and Foreign Commission President Gian Giacomo Migone,
who said Italy intended to recognize the island's independence as
soon as possible so as to remove any room for uncertainty which
could lead to further violence.
</P>
<P>
"By sending a multinational peacekeeping force to the island
Italy has in effect already recognized East Timor's independence,
but before it can officially recognize East Timor, a government
must be established there," Martelli said.
</P>
<P>
Martelli, who will travel in November to Indonesia and Dili,
the East Timor capital, reiterated that Italy wanted perpetrators
of crimes against the Timorese population to be punished and
recalled that it had voted in favour of a United Nations
commission to investigate the crimes.
</P>
<P>
Responding to a question on the military role of Italy's 600
troops currently stationed in East Timor, Martelli said soldiers
participating in the UN peacekeeping mission were authorized to
attack first in danger, unlike in Bosnia where the peace
contingent could only open fire in self-defense. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0331 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Wind Energy For Electricity Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, October 5 (Xinhua) -- Wind energy could provide 10
percent of the world's electricity requirements by 2020, create
1.7 million jobs and reduce global carbon dioxide emissions by
more than 10 billion tons, a report released Tuesday said.
</P>
<P>
Findings of the report indicate that a total of 1.2 million
Megawatts (MW) of wind power can be installed worldwide by 2020,
producing more than the total electricity consumption in Europe
today. "In Europe, one fifth of this total capacity would be
installed, creating a quarter of a million jobs," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The 1.2 million MW represents one fifth of 1998 worldwide
electricity consumption, highlighting the conservative approach
taken in the report of a business-as-usual world that doubles
electricity use by 2020.
</P>
<P>
The report, commissioned by Greenpeace, the European Wind
Energy Association and the Forum for Energy and Development,
unveiled their global energy blueprint at the Financial Times
World Renewable Energy Conference in Brussels, "the first major
business summit on renewable energy".
</P>
<P>
The three organizations called on all countries at next month's
UN Climate Convention meeting in Bonn to ensure that the Clean
Development Mechanism (CDM), outlined in the Kyoto Protocol
adopted in December 1997, promotes renewable technology transfer
and excludes nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
In order to achieve the 10 percent target, the report also
calls on world's governments to establish firm targets to remove
inherent electricity sector barriers, halt fossil fuel and nuclear
subsidies, and introduce a range of legally enforced mechanisms to
promote wind energy.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of the Kyoto Protocol signalled to the energy
industry the beginning of the phaseout of fossil fuels," said
Corin Millais, Greenpeace Renewable Energy Campaigner.
</P>
<P>
"Governments must now act to establish the regulatory framework
and set legally binding targets for renewables. There's no excuse
for inaction because wind power is an affordable, feasible,
mainstream global energy force that is able to substitute for
conventional fuels," Millais added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19991006.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-10-06 </DATE_TIME>
